comment: I love her lectures. She is clearly passionate about what she does but she can be a bit scatter brained. This makes it difficult to discern whats important and what isnt. Terms and names are very important on the tests. She will always test you with long quotations and ask who was speaking and where it came from. She is very willing to help you.
ratingTags: Accessible outside class--Graded by few things--Amazing lectures

comment: I really really like Professor Peek as a person, but her class was rough for me. The powerpoint is crammed with information, and the study guide for the final was over 5 pages long with terms before it was even filled out. Most of the terms were super obscure. We only have two papers in the class, but it took her a month and a half to grade them.
ratingTags: TEST HEAVY--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: An absolute treat. Peek is incredibly witty and makes every class enjoyable. Very doable tests -- a midterm and a final -- and she is more than happy to let you take your final during one of her other class' time slot if you have an issue with the time. Highly recommend, if only to hear her explain her kids' names (which is a great story).

Prof Peek is amazing, hands down. Very clear, very funny, and knows her stuff. While attendance isn't counted, you'll wanna go to class every day; from the earliest Greek past the age of Alexander, she makes history easy and fun. The tests are mildly challenging, but her TA holds excellent reviews. Please take from her -- you won't regret it.
Great teacher, great class, great experience. Would recommend.
Felicia is a great teacher and on top of that, she is a babe.  If you can find a class she is teaching, take it from her.

I loved Heather as a teacher! she is dedicated to helping us love and understand literature. Shes supper easy to talk to, and gives fantastic feedback on your writing. I definitely suggest taking from her.

I'm tired of grad student instructors. They act like they're the center of your universe because they're finally teaching. We have to keep a running journal, while reading stories and writing summarization reviews each week, while attending several reading workshops that, if not attended, will destroy our grade, while writing large papers each week

Ugh. I hated this class. Instructions were unclear and assignments did not list all requirements, so unless you were listening very carefully in class you might miss what you actually needed to do. There were multiple projects going on at the same time and it was just a lot more stressful than an introductory class needed to be.

Bro G has a lot of experience in his field. This was one of the most useful classes I took as a humanities major at BYU. Bro G helps you produce a basic design portfolio from nothing. But be prepared to speak up during class if you don't understand something; lectures are fast-paced and often hard to follow if you aren't willing to ask questions.
Super useful class and the final book project was so fun! Make sure to turn things in on time and don't be afraid to talk to the TA.
There isn't a lot of lecture time, mostly just time to work in class.  However, the class is pretty easy if you pay attention to instructions, and there is little homework outside of class.

Professor Gardner's class is not hard - but don't take it if you want to learn anything. His class can be stressful because he is so unclear about assignments, and his lectures are. so. boring. He doesn't really teach, he mostly just talks out loud and expects you to follow along. Easy A, but a complete and total waste of time.

Brother Gardner is such a nice guy, but his class was way more stressful than it needed to be. His expectations for your assignments (including due dates) aren't very clear. He rushes through some important instructions and it's pretty difficult to catch up if you miss anything.
Amazing teacher and now a friend! Extremely helpful in understanding and learning new concepts. Loved this class would recommend anyone to take this class from Brother Gardner!
great guy great teacher
Super easy class, all the lectures teach you exactly what will be on the test and you can buy the lecture slides at the book store! He does his best to make lectures engaging and pretty entertaining!

HOT, very attractive, husband material. and on top of all that a good and VERY generous professor. always open for one on one time in which he is very active. I recommend it to anyone who wants to get the ultimate experience from a language practicing it in many various types of enviroments.

Great class overall. Talal will really tries to help any way he can. Sometimes the work load can be a lot, but it'll be the same for any Arabic 101 course and he's willing to work with you if you fall behind. I would highly recommend taking it from him.
Great teacher. Native speaker. Really willing to help whenever possible.

He was a great teacher, always kept the class engaging and worked hard to make sure everyone was learning and involved. Understood the student's needs and knew how to cater to them. Would definitely recommend taking Arabic from him! (He is also a native speaker for extra points)

Professor Vincent is incredible! She is passionate about what she teaches and really cares about her students; she makes it clear she wants everyone to succeed. My writing skills and passion for writing and service have increased because of her and this class.

She makes you feel small. I learned a lot from her and she does help you getting set up before you accomplish stuff. I enjoyed all the resources she taught in class. She is an extremely hard grader. I never felt so belittled though it was frustrating.

Sister Vincent is a great teacher and makes this required writing class enjoyable and fun.  My only complaint is BYU allows concurrent high school students take the class.  Those in my section were never prepared, played on their phones during class, and as you can tell from their comments - too immature and not ready for college level work.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: I had to take this class because it was required in order to graduate.  I didn't like her teaching style, it was very difficult to understand. She was so demanding on what she wanted from us and there were so many papers to write, besides she's a tough grader.  Honestly had a really bad experience in this class...
ratingTags: Tough Grader--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--SO MANY PAPERS

comment: I just returned from an LDS mission and couldn't believe how much this class helped  prepare me. I am a better writer and communicator. I loved Sister Vincent and felt she was a great teacher; always prepared, very upfront about the requirements for each assignment, and provided plenty of office hours for assistance if I needed it.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Clear grading criteria

comment: Tonja is great. Dept. syllabus, grade rubric, etc. but she made the class interesting. Lots of videos from Youtube/movies/TV provided examples of good writing & helped improve my grade in other classes too. Reg office hrs, reviews, answered emails. If you didnt enjoy Tonja, didnt learn anything, or didnt get the grade you wanted - thats on you.

I have never worked with a professor who was so misunderstanding of students. Sometimes when I have tried to have a conversation with her, it seems like her mind is elsewhere. She is a horrible communicator, hopefully you never have to take a class from her.

I would not take this class from Tonja if I were you. She is always very unprepared. We were supposed to have writing conferences where we would look over my rough draft of a paper and when I got there she hadn't even read my paper. that happened twice! classes are boring. I didn't learn anything while taking this class.

Tonja was awesome. The class itself was fairly hard, but she was really helpful and worked with me a lot. She was flexible with deadlines when I was up front with her and she holds conferences regularly to help with papers about half-way through each unit. Lectures could be a little scattered, but overall they were helpful.

This teacher seemed very scatter-brained as she taught. She didn't seem to fully understand. When writing, she pushed for what she wanted you to write and not giving you freedom to write what you want, even if it would fail. There seemed to me that you could only imitate what she wanted which did not help me to grow as a writer. Classes seemed long

Randall has been one of my favorite professors I have ever had while attending BYU. He taught in a way that made even the hardest principles seem easy. He also provided ample opportunity to feel prepared for each test and gave out fair grades. He is also funny, and down to earth. I felt like I could relate to him, which made class more enjoyable.
Randall is awesome. He was a great teacher and super clear. Reviews are very salubrious, so make sure you go.
Randall Reese is the best math teacher ever! He takes a lot of his own time to give great reviews and actually cares how his students do. He redeemed the math department for me!

This instructor has been the best math teacher I've ever had, all faculty math teachers have been ineffective in explaining concepts when compared to him. His ability to recognize students doubts or misunderstandings and then address them was great. The best math teacher I have had at BYU. Made sure we were prepared for tests.

Randall really takes the time to help students. He gives multiple hours of very helpful test review for each midterm on his own time. I really enjoyed this class. And they should get this guy doing stand up as a side job. He is super hilarious. The final is awful, but he has no control over that, so not much to bring him down on there.

Randall is a great teacher. We identified well with him, he helped us see where we would have trouble, he was patient and took time to answer all of our questions, and put our concerns as a priority.  He would take time to help every student. Very good teacher. Genuinely cared about the students.

I'm really glad to have taken this class from Randall Reese. He went out of his way to help all of us do well, whether it was on homework or tests. I enjoyed his no nonsense approach to preparing for tests, and the enjoyable atmosphere he created in class.
He is super unclear, and in order to pass this intro class, you pretty much have to a programming master already. Good luck.

He is a super nice guy, however he is a Python programmer so he doesn't know C++ well enough to answer most questions. He loves programming so when those who have programmed their whole lives ask random questions, he spends tons of time on those, further confusing everyone else. Get someone else if you're new to programming. Also time intensive.

Brother Lund is a very nice man, but the way he tried to explain things weren't always the best. He tried a lot to help, always willing to take questions, staying late if necessary. Labs took a LOT of time and weren't very clear, TAs were only sometimes helpful. If you put all the time that's needed into the class you will get a good grade.

He was very nice and tried his best to help answer questions but usually just ended up confusing whoever was asking even more by talking about material that the class didn't cover.  There are some pretty tough lab assignments as part of the class and the TAs were lifesavers - I never would have figured out the homework with just the professor.
The dude tries to "teach Spanish in Spanish" and half the class slept through every lecture.  The TA's are your only hope.

I had no experience with coding before this class, and I did not think this class was too bad. Most coding classes are not going to be interesting, and this one did not defy the norm. However, Brother Lund was always willing to help you out. Any time you had a problem with a grade, or anything he was there for you. He is super nice and very clear.

With the criteria for 142 being pretty inflexible, Professir Lind does a great job. He obviously cares about his students and will do what he can to defend his class from the others. Labs are the same no matter what class you take, and aren't that hard if you sit down and take the time. With no previous programming experience, I did well.
My first and favorite English professor. She got me a job and encouraged me to continue in the major. Wonderful teacher and person.

Hardest part of this class is that she has really high standards for papers. But, she's very helpful during office hours, making an A on a paper totally do-able. Prof. Eyring is so good at making difficult material accessible and at building a syllabus that is interesting and fun (not just the same early American texts you've read 12 times already)

Eyring was awesome! Difficult class, but if you enjoy intellectual conversation and expanding your world views this class is extremely enjoyable. Lectures feel like a large in depth group discussion where opinions and comments matter more that crossing off the boxes to get through the lecture.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Respected--Get ready to read

comment: Dr. Eyring is brilliant. While the class is lecture-heavy, if you listen, you will learn a ton. She knows what she is talking about. What's more is she cares for each of her students and gives really helpful feedback. She is willing to work with you. And she is just a gem of a person overall.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Skip class? You won't pass.--Caring

comment: Helped me love a class I didn't think I would like

She's a great teacher and very knowledgeable. Her lectures are usually very advanced and confusing. Notes are mandatory if you want to do well on the tests (only one midterm and the final). Helpful feedback on papers. TONS of reading, so be aware of that. She's great though, and very open to all viewpoints and perspectives.

Dr Eyring is one of the best professors I've had at BYU. She prepares for her classes so well and gives really great lectures and facilitates great discussions in her class. The tests were hard but there weren't many of them. We had to turn in reading responses every class but if you do them you get credit. I 100% recommend taking her  class.

Professor Eyring is an amazing professor who truly cares about her students and their academic success. I thoroughly enjoyed her class and actually enrolled for another one of her classes! She is a fair grader, and validates all of her students comments and gracefully incorporates them into the discussion. The exams are difficult, but doable.

Dr. Eyring actually cares about her students and wants them to learn. She asks for feedback from the class and wants to know how she can improve. She is really funny and class goes by quickly. She incorporates a lot of class discussion rather than just lecture. I wish I could take her for every English class at BYU!

I adore this woman; she is such a fantastic teacher. She is incredibly intelligent, kind, funny, and organized. I learned so much in this class. There's a lot of reading (like every English class) and a short paragraph response due every class period, but every assignment was well worth it. She cares about her students and gives excellent feedback.
She is amazing! not only is she gorgeous and nice, but also a great teacher. Lots of student participation. I think I want to be her when I grow up.

I adore her. Her class is challenging, but she does it to make you stretch yourself. She helped me numerous times, and always made herself available, even out of her office hours when I couldn't come. She validates everyone's comments and opinions no matter how dumb you may feel when you contribute.

Her tests are usually extremely hard, and her grading is tough, but you won't learn the basics better from anyone else. She's engaging, well-liked, and knowledgeable about all of the topics. Discussion is everything in this class, and it works well for her. What a fantastic teacher; I would take a class from her again.

Professor Eyring is so knowledgeable in English. She will learn your name and talk to you personally if you need help. You will get a good grade so long as you show up to class, participate, and make an effort on all assignments. Don't fall behind on the readings! If you want to learn English take Eyring!

Besides simply being an extraordinarily nice person, Dr. Eyring is really helpful during class time. Her lessons help you understand everything from the reading and learn how to apply your knowledge to a variety of topics.
Do not take her class. Her class is boring and frustrating.  Her lectures are long and assignment instructions are vague. Assignments are harshly graded.
This is a super chill class! This class isn't time consuming and it's easy to get an A if you simply go to class. And she's the nicest lady!
Avoided this teacher at all cost!!! Most boring teacher I have ever had. She decides your grade based on if she likes you or not.

Avoid this professor at all cost. You can't earn your grade. She decides it. She comes out and says that in the first day of class. She starts to dock you points on papers and assigments if she doesn't like you. She picks favorites and doesn't like anyone who has a "fun" personality.

the ultimate cyclingspinning diva. He's very fabulous and over the top which makes this class hilarious. Interesting selection of music on some days, but for the most part matches music very well with whatever workout we have that day.

I have had a few cycling instructors through various classes and Brent has been the best! He is well planned for each class and has great playlists to go right along with the workout. Brent helped me stay motivated even on days that I didn't want to work out. I have seen a difference in my cycling and learned to love it even more than I did before.

Brent was amazing. He made every workout new and exciting. I always felt motivated to come to class as well as participate in class. I saw a lot of results personally in my fitness based on the workouts he provided. I would definitely take this class from him again.

One of the highlights of my time at college. Brent goes far above what is expected by an instructor. He makes class fun and is always engaged with everybody in the class. He is basically the Mary Poppins of spinning. Taking his class felt a lot like you were in some sort of exclusive club where they had hired the best instructor money could buy.

Taking this class was one of the best decisions I have ever made. It was hard, but Brent motivates you to push through and I improved so much in cycling. Every class was different with great playlists, workout types, dance lights and even movie days. There is a feedback link that you can submit music and workout requests too.

Great teacher! Comes up with different workouts every day and tries to keep things different. He has an online survey you can take out so you can let him know if you didn't like one of the types of workouts. He does push you harder than the other cycling teachers, but its worth it.   Also really funny!

This class is such a blast.  Brent makes working out fun even though his workouts are tough!  He tries to make each class period different and exciting with new workouts, dancing, arm weights, disco lights, feedbackrequests, themed playlists, random facts, etc.   It really is so much fun in his class.
Alex is amazing! He cares SO much for every student. His teaching is unique because he shows up to class not just to lecture but to learn from his students. He really gets to know every student.

Alex is an excellent teacher who really cares about his students and the topics he teaches. His grading seems reasonable until you realize that each of the few assignments in the class will seriously hurt your grade if you fail to notice any number of minor things (A is 95%). Don't expect to ace this class and you'll love it.

Alex is an excellent teacher and keeps class extremely interesting. Here is the struggle- everything is graded by the TA's. Which is understandable except that who grades your papers makes or breaks you because they are very inconsistent between each other. The tests are fair and the major paper really isn't too bad if you work consistently on it
ratingTags: Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.--Test heavy

comment: Alex is one of the best professors I've had. The research paper is difficult but he meets with you and tells you everything you should change. Tests are difficult but THE MOST FAIR exams I have ever seen at BYU. They are hard but straight forward questions, not a single one was I wondering when we ever learned about it. He is just the best person.

I LOVE ALEX. He was the best teacher. He engages his students, really cares about our learning process and is a very reasonable grader. He throws out bad test questions. There is one big research project that takes a lot of time and effort and is graded pretty harshly. I love, love, loved coming to class every day. Take this class from Alex!

Alex is a pretty young professor and as such, remembers what it was like to be a student. His assignments are fair and he gives tons of helpful feedback, as well as allowing a note card on the midterm and final. Attendance isn't mandatory but extremely helpful, it's hard to ace a test without it. One of my favorite professors at BYU.

His classes are discussion-based, and he writes the test questions based off of what is discussed, so be sure to attend lecture and participate!  He presents the material very clearly, and is so fun to learn from!  One of my favorite classes at BYU!

Alex is a wonderful instructor. He meets with students individually to review their research paper and gives the opportunity to rewrite it to improve your grade. His tests had a lot of short answer response, but you get an index card, and he asks students for feedback on the tests to improve them. He'll push you, but has realistic expectations.

He is a great teacher who really cares about his students. He is young and a new teacher, so he knows what students want and need. His classes are interesting and he does a lot of fun activities and games. His tests are easy cause you get to take a 3x5 notecard for the multi. choice, but you do need to go to class for the short answer part.

Alex is an awesome professor! Very accommodating to his students. Very fair grader. Class lectures are engaging and full of discussion. He allows a 3x5 notecard on his tests. He writes all test questions right after class so there are no surprises. He also evaluates all test questions and will throw out those that are unfairtoo tricky.

If you want a class that actually prepares you for the workforce, this is one of the best. Former student here, this is a difficult & time-consuming class... but it is the most realistic to what your future bosses actually value! In real-life the most valuable work is where you actually have to think and come up with a solutions without guidance.
ratingTags: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.--Group projects

comment: Professor Heaton is hands down the best professor I've had at BYU. He is incredibly knowledgeable and goes so much deeper than most professors. His only goal is to educate you to the best of his ability so you can go make an impact in the world. I took both of his classes and they are difficult, but don't let that deter you. You will learn SO much!

Prof. Heaton's class is the best class I took at BYU. It is the "capstone" class of the finance program because it forces you to use everything you have learned from the finance core and apply it to real world scenarios. Be prepared to work, these cases are no joke. However, he encourages group work, so take this class with a friend/study-buddy.

Take this class from Heaton. The HBS case study method he uses is the most productive way to teach material that will stay with you forever. Be ready to prep a case every week, take a quiz on the case you prepped, and take random current event quizzes. Grading based all on quizzes, how well you support your claims in class, and optional final

Professor Heaton is a very smart man and has many experiences to share from his impressive career. Unfortunately, much of the class period is comprised of him going on many tangents about himself and failing to effectively explain the subject topic. Be ready to prepare a case study for each class period, with difficult pop quiz each class period.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: One of my favorite professors at BYU, very honest and sincere, doesn't just want you to learn the material but learn how to apply it via his case study method. Get ready to accept that you're not going to understand everything right away. Just enjoy the strategic application of the financial theory that you're given in your core classes.

Hands down the most brilliant professor at BYU. As mentioned, he'll treat you to the Heaton Beatin' where he cold calls in his class and gets all up in your face playing the devil's advocate with your argument. Purely case studies. Savor the moments learning from a mind like his.

Brilliant professor who used to teach at HBS. Known for the "Heaton beatin'" where he asks you a bunch of questions, but he's really a gentle giant who's just testing your knowledge or assumptions. Having no midterms and an optional final is nice for obvious reasons, but your grade is more based on homework preparation than what you actually learn.
Best TA ever!  Love this guy
Josh was really invested in this class and in us, his students. It really made all the difference in my experience with this class.
would definitely take again, such a cool dude and an awesome TA
He respects my affinity for y'all. 'Nuff said.
Josh was great! He had fun games in class and his way of teaching really helped me learn. I was apprehensive about my ability to learn Russian, but Josh made it so much easier!
Josh is super fun and knows how to connect to students. Has great ways of teaching Russian as well as how to study them. Had creative games for in-class participation.

Josh. What can be said about this man that hasn't already been said? For one, he was always there to help. Even when he was home or doing something else, he would answer a question or concern. Josh is the man. A friend, a scholar, and a sexy beast. Need I say more?
Josh is hot.
Joshua Prince. Hilarious. Reliable. Clear-cut. Super helpful. Made class engaging. Hot as that crop of fiery orange hair. Overall awesome TA. Too bad someone else already put a ring on it.

Josh is probably the freaking best TA I have ever had, or will ever have, at BYU.  He was engaging and knew us as his friends, not as his students. No one else will quite measure up, and I'm genuinely sad that for RUSS 102 I have to have a different TA. Why did you have to graduate, Josh?   And he's even hotter than his gingery hair.

Josh Prince worked really hard to teach this class. Never phoned it in for a moment. Always was prepared with examples and explanations of the concepts, and anticipated the problems the students would have with the material.

Scott is an absolutely joke for a professor. He should not be teaching any class at BYU. The tests are written by the TAs, are all short answer, and require a LOT of memorization. They told us the papers would help boost our grade at the end of the semester-the average paper grade was a B-. He cannot even write himself.  AVOID HIM AT ALL COSTS.

Professor Baird shows real interest in his students, which I respect. As other reviews mention, his assignments are long and rubrics aren't clear. He frequently mentions new expectations which can be frustrating. However, he is new to teaching the course and I'd expect the structure to improve. Meet with him outside of class!

I will be honest, a lot of the reviews on here are biased one way or the other. Baird has a unique teaching style, but you will learn a lot. He has awesome real-world experience that makes lectures interesting. The assignments are confusing, so if you need clarification, ask to meet one on one. He is very nice and will gladly help you out.
Not a good class at all.  Assignments were very ambiguous and graded toughly.  Instructor is an awesome business man and a poor professor.

By far the worst experience I've had in 3 years at BYU. Professor is extremely unclear. Assignment directions are ambiguous, but he is a very tough grader. Tests are also super difficult. He is very disrespectful of his students, and obviously doesn't really care about helping them do well in his class. Get. Out. Now. While you still can. TERRIBLE.

Worst class that I have ever taken. Always changes assignment's requirements right before they are due. There is no clear grading style. He is arrogant and will simply give a bad grade because he has a bad day. There is no logic in his though process. He is very disrespectful of student's opinions and views. Overall - he is terrible.

I hate to give him a bad grade, because I got some great insight from is lectures. What is frustrating is that he is specific in what he wants but extremely unclear about expectations. Grading is unfair. Pro Tip: The TA will tell you to only write what is necessary for responses on the test, NOT TRUE! Best strategy is to write tons of BS & pray.

Awesome professor! I learned a ton in his class! He is a great speaker and lecturer. Do the assignments and you will do well. It's not a hard class.  I love his teaching style, wish he taught more classes.

Dr. Baird was a real inspiration. He is very passionate in his teaching style. He has high expectation but goes out of his way to help. Tough class but I learned more about me and organizational effectiveness than any other class in my business core. I would highly recommend this class and Dr. Baird as a professor.
This guy is by far the worst teacher I have had at BYU. Nothing more

Worst experience I've had at BYU. He's not afraid to give someone 25% on a paper. Papers galore. The rubrics, assignment descriptions on syllabus, and in-class instructions on papers are all different.  The rubric he uses to grade an assignment is different from any rubric provided before assignment is due. Take it from anyone else.

He is not consistent in assignments, grading, or teaching. He has several assignment descriptions and the correct one is not always posted before the assignment is due, but you are still expected to follow it. His lectures are mostly BS with some useful things mentioned occasionally. He changed the finals the last week of class.

Dr. Amott is one of my favorite professors thus far at BYU. As someone who is well into a science major, it was really refreshing to get some culture. The principals of analyzing art Amott teaches will overlap in other areas of you life, and it makes the world a more interesting place. The class was not too challenging, pop quizzes can hurt though.

David Amott was by far the most caring professor I have had at BYU. I am far from an Art History major and I can honestly say it is one thing I am not passionate about. All I really ask for in a professor is that they be passionate about what they are teaching and that they genuinely care about their students. David rocks both of those qualities!

Professor Amott is very passionate about art history, to the level that it is hilarious. I have signed up for and attended many art history classes before and I always dropped them because the professors were ridiculously tough and boring. Amott is entertaining and, honestly, it does not take much to get a good grade. Show up for attendance quizzes

I did pass out in class a couple times but because Professor Amott is a very passionate teacher, it's not a common occurrence. Reviews with TA are essential for  acing tests. The tests aren't hard, just do what the TA's say.  Participation is necessary. Show up to class and skim the book and you'll do fine. Overall, helped me enjoy art.

I wish I could take all of my classes from Dr Amott.  He is engaging, entertaining and hilarious.  Unfortunately, apart from him, this class is like weeding a cactus garden; an extremely slow and painful process, where even after you are done, you still have to pick out all of the tiny needles that are still in your hands for a long time afterward.

Professor Amott takes an inherently boring subject in Art History and makes it come to life with unrivaled enthusiasm and humor.  The class covers a wide span of subject matter and rewards detailed note-taking and the completion of reading assignments.  Kind of a tough class in general, but worth it: it double-counts, completing two GE credits.

I. Love. Dr. Wimmer. Do anything you can to take a class from her or your experience at BYU will not be complete. She knows her stuff well and will teach you amazing things. She is accessible outside of class (GO TALK WITH HER, it will change your life...+snacks!) and wants the best for you. Put effort into her class and assignments--it is worth it

Dr. Wimmer is AMAZING! She genuinely cares about your success! Talk to her about anything and she will do her best to help you. The class is not bad. There are several papers, but you know in advance. She makes it very doable. Keep up on everything and you will be very successful. You will be enriched academically and spiritually. Take from her!!!
Pass/ fail Participation - Reading questions - Attend most lectures The information in this class is awesome. I love that I can just learn instead of stressing about grades.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Caring--LECTURE HEAVY

comment: I didn't feel like the homework assignments prepared me well for the test, which was very much conceptual. Dr. Cook didn't really respect my ideas and concerns. He does answer your questions, but I left more confused after he "answered" them. If this were an optional class, I would not take it. Overall, an "I could care less" class.

Dr. Cook is sensible and helpful. He does a good job teaching challenging material and makes sure to take the time to help everyone understand. His tests are hard, but he lets you use a page of notes. Daily reading quizzes and homework assignments always end up taking more time than you'd expect, so don't put them off til the last minute.

Sometimes we would get behind in class so we would end up having to rush material and it wouldn't make sense, but Dr. Cook is one of the most reasonable ChEn teachers at BYU. Really great guy, knows his stuff, and very willing to help you. He's also good about giving points back on tests.
One of the better ChemE professors and his MatSci course has been my favorite ChemE class yet! (Of course the competition isn't high) Great teacher though his research is incredible!

I took this class, hoping to strengthen my testimony of Christ, and instead ended up focusing more on tedious details so that I wouldn't lose points on assignments. I've never had a teacher be so specific about the content of my posts before. Be very careful with reading instructions. He likes to try and trick you.

Brother Carter is really helpful if you are diligent about going in and asking for help. His tests were online and on the honor code. They are pretty tricky though and he focuses on specific quotes and will switch small words. It's a seminary class. If you want a deeper understanding of the Book of Mormon or an easy A, don't take from  Carter.

Brother Carter was one of the greatest professors I've ever had. He cares more about your personal development and understanding of gospel topics than making this a difficult, college-level religion course. As long as you attend class, do the readings, and honestly pay attention, you'll be fine

Professor Carter is a great teacher! He makes lectures interesting and enjoyable. The class if very easy if you show up to class and study the powerpoints a little bit before the quizzes. The only thing I didn't like was you have to make sure to read the quiz questions very well because some of them or designed to trick you. I definitely recommend!
Has a lot of weird questions about specific quotes and things he personally thinks are important. Very fun and friendly and a great guy but seems like he tries to find ways to complicate the class.

He loves true false questions and will change one or two of the important words to get you. Loves "gotcha" questions.  He focuses on doctrine of the church and supplemental readings more than on the actual Book of Mormon. It's a seminary class. If you want a deeper understanding of the Book of Mormon or an easy A, don't take from Brother Carter.

If you liked seminary, Bro Carter is for you. Take careful notes in class because he doesn't post the important information from the slideshow online, and the quizzes are almost exactly like the slideshows from class. If you space on a quiz or other assignment, he'll let you do it late most of the time.
Really good guy, but good luck getting help if you need it. Wouldn't even talk to me before the midterm, probably going to fail, but the glorified seminary teacher in him won't help me at all.

Fantastic teacher, who creates a very spiritual atmosphere every class. Many of his quiz and test questions are taken almost word-for-word of things he says in class,  so pay close attention and you'll do well.

All his tests and quizzes are online but closed note and book.  This means theyre tough unless you study an hour for them beforehand (he provides PowerPoints and stuff).  If you want an A you definitely need to attend class and pay attention because some quiz and test questions will just be from his lectures.   You can feel the spirit in class.

Bro. Carter is a really great teacher! I loved him; took two semesters with him and it was worth it. You always feel the spirit in lectures and he is always open to questions. He does give you three free absences but I suggest showing up to class anyway, he's that good!

Brother Carter is great and really funny. I liked him so much that I'm taking another class from him next semester. His quizzes are very difficult because they are so specific on small details, however they are almost always word for word from the powerpoints

Brother Carter nice and funny and cares about his students and the gospel a lot. That being said, i probably wouldn't take a class from him again. In lecture he often asks questions that are supposedly open ended but he is only looking for one specific answer which personally drives me CRAZY! His quizes are hard and very specific to being in class

Brother Carter really cares about his students. He wants everyone to grow closer to Christ, and therefore, increases the amount of attention needed. If you pay attention and take notes, you'll do well. And no, he doesn't give pop quizzes like the person below said, he gives weekly quizzes with fair warning on Learning Suite

Brother Karter is a great guy, but he rushes through lectures and gets off topic pretty easily.  His quizzes are tough and you literally have to listen to specific words he says or you will fail, and also the tests and quizzes are based on his opinions, not on actual doctrine.  He's great but I probably wouldn't take again.

Bro Carter is the Man! I enjoyed his class so much. He's caring and really loves each of his students. I have become so much closer to Christ and learned so much that I didn't think I could. But yes, Amazing! Take him!

Professor Carter was great.  I actually felt the spirit in this religion class.  Pay attention during lecture as many things that are talked about in lecture come up in the weekly quizzes and tests.  I got an A and it wasnt that hard to get it

Bro. Carter is an inspiring professor.  If you take decent notes and study them before you take each quiz you'll easily get an A.  Everything was done using LearningSuite. Almost all midterm and final questions come from these weekly quizzes, so studying for those is cake.  Weekly reflection assignments are simple.  Overall this was a great class.

Bro Carter is a great guy who really wants to bring his students closer to Christ. His weekly quizzes were usually pretty tough, and you have to pay very close attention to his lectures, he often rushes through a topicscripture that ends up on the quizzes. There were weekly and end-of-term writing assignments as well, but he's easy on grading them

This was not my favorite class. The quizzes are more about New Testament class than the New Testament (questions such as "Which points were on this slide in Tuesday's lecture?" or "What was the focus of our discussion Monday about this?"). I feel like that inhibited learning on the topic as more focused was placed on the minutia than on the gospel.

Interesting teacher, Made new testament interesting at least. Quizzes were a pain because of little details from the readings or comments in class that you need to remember but he was spiritual yet funny. Not a bad teacher.

His pop quizzes are really hard and tricky. You really, really have to read everything extremely close and listen to all of his little nuances in lecture or you won't pass the quizzes or midterms. Less about what the scriptures mean and more about little   wordplays and whatnot.
Bro. Carter's lectures are very inspirational! This is the first religion class where I actually felt like my testimony grew. Test questions come from quizzes, so be sure to go to class everyday.

Carter was super insightful and understanding. He knew his students pretty well, and it seemed like everyone in the class was interested and participated in his lessons. There were weekly quizzes on the reading, and sometimes they were tricky. He drops a couple, and that helps a lot. Tests are not bad-he draws from the weekly quizzes. Good class!

Brother Carter was a very spiritual teacher and the tests were easy. However, lectures were often pretty dull. You have to go to almost every single class, you only get 3 absences a semester. There are quizzes every week IN CLASS, and he tends to ask trick questions-- on purpose. Plus, he never tells you what day the quiz will be.
his religion class was super insightful. he focuses on spiritual and factual factors. the workload is super light and the discussions in class are always really great

Dr Auman is super caring, and a very good person. However, her class required a MINIMUM 30 hour project (it took me 40 hours) and a ton of time outside of class. Her lectures are boring. Theres no midterm, so I didnt know how the final was formatted. If you take this class, be ready to put in a lot of time, and study a lot before the final.
ratingTags: Participation matters--So many papers--Graded by few things

comment: Her assignments were fair and reasonable. I also like how she believes in donating her time to do genealogy for others As a note, Professor Auman is slightly passive aggressive. It seems to me that there are times when she acts happy but is actually quite irked. She also won't continue talking until there aren't any distractions going on in class.

Professor Auman is a great professor. She explains things nicely and is very helpful. For this class, you will have a 50 hour research project and be required to write several papers, but none of them are too difficult. She is extremely helpful and gives you plenty of time. I would highly recommend her!
ratingTags: ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--SO MANY PAPERS--Amazing lectures

comment: Karen Auman's class is focused on writing/english, not necessarily history. All assignments and exams are written papers. If you don't know how to write, this class is not for you. Some things she says are false or not strongly supported but she stands by them as if they were facts.
It was almost all based on readings. gives pop quizzes in class on occasion based on reading assignments. Memorize the book to get an A.

Professor Auman was an adequate teacher.  Her expectations were fairly clear and there were not too many assignments.  She did explain the material.  However, her lectures were not very interesting and she taught a cookie-cutter version of history.  She never really challenged my perspectives and wasn't very open minded.

Professor Auman was an adequate teacher.  Her expectations were fairly clear and there were not too many assignments.  She did explain the material.  However, her lectures were not very interesting and she taught a cookie-cutter version of history.  She never really challenged my perspectives or shed new light on the subject matter.

Pr Auman makes US History soooo interesting! I thought I would hate this class but it ended up being one of my favorites! Her lectures are very clear and she is always ready to answer questions. Sometimes the readings can be long, but always very interesting and carefully chosen. If you take good notes and do the readings, you should do fine.

Dr. Richards is a musical genius. I love his class because you're excited to be there. No tough homework, 1 some-what hard mid-term. He helps you become excited about what he's talking about. I'd definitely take another class from him.

Take a class from Dr. Richards. It's an incredible experience. He approaches things unconventionally, more open minded and participation-based than most classes. Class is personal, casual, and a genuinely fun experience. If you like rigidly structured classes, it's not for you, but it is if you like to learn from a personal & meaningful standpoint.

Honestly, Rachel is the best.  She's super chill and is always willing to help out.  There's barely any homework and only 3 essays throughout the semester.  She gives you a rubric before each essay, and as long as you follow it, you'll easily get an A.
Rachel was a great teacher and I would totally recommend her. She is very relaxed, and grades fairly easy if you show that you put time and thought into your papers.

Great teacher, makes class more interesting. Only have to write 3 papers for all Writing 150 classes. Gives extra credit opportunities to go to the writing center before turning in papers. Replies to your emails and is helpful. Fair with grading and allows you to re-write your papers if you aren't happy with the grade. Defiantly would recommend!

Rachel was awesome!!  She's very intelligent and knows what she's talking about. However, she doesn't expect you to know everything.  She gives great feedback on papers and is always super helpful if something isn't clear. I would definitely take from her again!

Professor Wilson is a really nice person. For this class, however, the grading is pretty hard core. If you are somebody who wants to breeze through an easy writing class, he is not your guy. On the flip side, if you really want to come out of a class with some legitimate portfolio ready papers, consider Prof. Wilson.
Prof Wilson is such a good guy, really knows his stuff, really caring, and wants to help you understand the concepts and succeed. 10/10 Class

Really great teacher and knows his stuff! Lots of reading and quizzes that require you to be specific. Classes are more about doing case studies than actual lectures. Although tests matter, projects also contribute to a lot of your grade. You do have to put a little more effort to get an A in this class though. However, I really enjoyed it overall

Wilsons 320 class is very applicable to the field. I love his grading system for assignments He has you turn in an ungraded first draft, then gives feedback, and then has you turn in the final. He really wants you to learn the material. He tries not to give useless assignments.

You have to work super hard but it's completely worth it. Prof Wilson wants you to succeed and is gonna give you the feedback you need to make that happen. Expect to go through a lot of drafts but at the end you'll have portfolio-worthy pieces. Highly recommend

One of the best professors I've taken at BYU! Such a caring guy, loves to interact with his students, and will always listen to you if you have questions. Tough class, and we read the whole textbook and part of another, but worth it. I feel like what I learned will stick with me. 10/10 would take him again!
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--Caring

comment: Professor Wilson teaches a tough class. But unlike any other class I have ever taken at BYU, his class taught me more real life skills than ANY other class by far. He is highly organized, professional and sympathetic to those who work hard to succeed (or get an A). I highly recommend meeting with him for grades you're not happy with.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: A very time-intensive class, but one that will actually prepare you for the real world. Professor Wilson is super innovative and I really respect him for that. He's understanding and he's doesn't just do things for no reason like some professors do. He's a real tough grader, but if you listen to his feedback, then you'll become a much better writer

Great professor. Have had him twice. He is a tough grader but very specific with what he wants. He is willing to go over what you missed though and is really helpful. Expect LOTS of reading. Very on the ball and expects you to be too.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS

comment: Professor Wilson has been disrespectful towards students. His emails will leave you angry and then afraid to see him in class. He prides himself on grading harder than any other professor and this class was the least important class I've taken at BYU. Not worth the homework and headache.

Excellent teacher. Learned more in his class than any other comms class. He is beyond helpful, listens to every question you have, and wants you to do good. His tests are difficult but he  helps you a lot. Wish I could take all comms classes through him!

Wilson was a great teacher and wonderful guy. He gave you a ton of feedback on your work though sometimes you got a lower grade than expected. If you visit with him he gives great pointers on how to improve your writing. You will have to learn some of the adobe products. No tests or quizzes but a bit of reading. Stellar guy. Would take again.

I love this class! Brother Woodward is an exceptional teacher (and possibly a genius) when it comes to teaching religion classes. And he is absolutely HILARIOUS! He makes going to class actually enjoyable.

You get failed on assignments for not showing up in class even if the assignments are completed and turned in on time. Your graded on the quality of notes you take and get failed if they were not done in class. It doesn't matter why you were unable to attend.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--Tough grader

comment: I believe that Brother Woodward is definitely the best teacher to take this class from. I have had other religion teachers, and I can say that Brother Woodward has been my favorite teacher so far. I even signed up to take another class from him next semester.

I had Bro Woodward for The Eternal Family class. He teaches very clearly and also adds humor to his lectures. He gives students great counsel from the prophets and scriptures about the things we cover in class! Some of the reading is really long, so dont procrastinate assignments. Other than that, I learn a lot from his teaching!

TAKE PROFESSOR WOODWARD FOR ALL RELIGION CLASSES POSSIBLE. I have never enjoyed a class more than his.  His class is extremely organized and he gives you everything you need to succeed. All possible exam questions are given before each class, and he gives VERY in-depth reviews. This man is absolutely hilarious. He makes the class enjoyable.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Hilarious--Amazing lectures

comment: Prof. Woodward has weekly quizzes, written assignments and attendance points. The lectures are interesting and shares new facts about the BOM. But  quizzes are SUPER difficult and questions are not very clear, you will have to read the chapters 3 times to even see what he wants you to from the BOM.

He helped me better understand controversial topics in church history which significantly strengthened my testimony. He used great sources to back up everything he taught. Always willing to stay and talk about personal concerns or questions/doubts. He genuinely cared about me. One of the best teachers I have had so far!

Professor Woodward is a fantastic teacher. He is very solid. He knows his stuff and he doesn't really mess around. He is hilarious, however. His class is set up in such a way that you know exactly what to expect. All the quizzes and tests are open note, open book. His class isn't the easiest, but if you show up and do the work, you will get an A.

I would recommend Brother Woodard to everyone!!! His class is very straight forward. His tests are straight from the study guide. If you go to the review you will pass the test. I have never learned so much in a religion class. My testimony was strengthened so much! Beware of the paper at the end though... start working on it early!

Bro Woodward is the best BOM professor at BYU. I would highly recommend that you take his class. His tests are easy if you go to the reviews. His class is entertaining and insightful. The hardest part of the class was the BOM paper, but it is doable. TAKE WOODWARD.

Brother Woodward seems to be a good teacher, but I feel like a bad LDS person. His Purposes of the Book of Mormon paper is impossible. I do not agree with a lot of his teachings, just because my testimony is SO based on the atonement, and we never seemed to talk about it. I'm sure other people like him but he is not my cup of tea. Good luck.

Such an amazing class! Don't miss out. Brother Woodward is hilarious and his stories actually help you remember. He gives you a study guide for the tests and then holds review sessions where he gives you most of the answers. Only a few points in class so it is easy to have your grade slip from an A to A-.  Take this class!

Woodward's class is an Easy A. What I didn't enjoy is Woodward preaching his own doctrine, and he talks about the gospel as if it makes him superior. It bothered me how he asks students how they are going to change the world, and said he hoped for them to figure it out when they didn't plan to. His assumptions about human behavior are very poor.

Woodward is by far the best religion professor at BYU. Not only are his tests 100% cake if you go to his test reviews, he is incredibly engaging in lecture and certainly keeps you wanting to come to class. Weekly chapter write-ups aren't tough at all, but there is a 4 page single-spaced paper that is relatively tough.

His witty comments makes class enjoyable and he has such a strong testimony. On his study guides, he makes it very clear as to what  material will be on his tests. There is one term paper and each week there are page long chapter insights that are due, both assignments are fairly easy. You fill out your attendance and reading on Learning Suite.

He's a great teacher! Entertaining and makes things easy to understand. The tests are just like the study guides and he does reviews where he goes over the study guides. No quizzes, just self assessed attendance. One term paper that's not hard. Weekly chapter insights where you give opinions on assigned chapters. Again, tests are easy.

Awesome professor! I personally found some awesome application in the scriptures in his class and filling out the weekly D&C section summaries. I looked forward to class and the reading. He's very funny and real. Hardest part was the law of consecration paper but he grades very generously and I learned a lot doing it! Take D&C from him for sure!

Be prepared for a lot of reading. It's all good, but sometimes it will seem overwhelming. However, he is a hilarious teacher, he knows his stuff really well, and will always talk to you after class if you need help. Tests are straight forward, and the homework is easy. An essay on the law of consec. is prob the hardest part, but it was great.

Bro. Woodward is hilarious, inspirational and amazing professor. He really applies the D&C to you and makes it real. His presentations are very well put together, and he outlines what he wants you to know before class. There is a paper about the Law of Consecration and two exams, which were fairly easy if you go to class. Take D&C or BoM from him!

Professor Woodward is an amazing teacher! He really helped my understand the D&C for the first time in my life. He always brought the spirit into the classroom! Assignments and tests aren't too hard. He sets you up to be successful in his class.

I'm so sad that the semester is winding down, because this is my favorite class! Prof. Woodward has been my favorite teacher here at BYU. He is hilarious, and has really brought the D&C to life for me. I've learned so many things, and have felt the spirit so powerfully this semester. He has a great way of relating the scriptures to his students.

I LOVED Brother Woodward!!! His class was relatively easy, and he curved the midterm. He's a great teacher, and he makes his lectures interesting and funny. I would definitely take a class from him again

I took D&C and BoM from him and I'd take them both again. The weekly write ups are not difficult, do it and you get full points. There is one paper due and if you go talk to him, he will go through the whole thing with you. A midterm and a final, all the answers he gives you in class, if you miss anything he will give you the answers in test review

Professor Woodward is so funny but still respects the scriptures. The grading criteria was very clear and we knew what to expect. His test review sessions were also very helpful. There was a lot of reading, but that's what happens if you take it Spring term. I would definitely take this class again, it really brought the Spirit into my life.

Bro. Woodward is a hilarious guy, and  I really enjoyed his lectures. There were "section summaries" due once a week, and there was one paper on the Kirtland temple. Unfortunately,  a lot of his test questions seemed like trick questions, and multiple answers could be easily justified, so I felt like I had to read his mind.

He's a great professor.  I would love to take another class from him for sure.  A lot of religion classes are just easy A's but you have to work a little for this one.  If you do every assignment though, you should be fine.  He is really eager to help students and want you to succeed.  If you actually want to learn, then this is a great class.
A fair amount of reading and memorization, but expectations are very clear. Know the study guides and you're fine. Tougher grader on papers.

There aren't a lot of tests, but the ones that he does give are hard. You have to know the information. A lot of reading, both reading the section and a section background. He is always willing to help.

There are daily reading assignments about the background to the sections. There are 2 papers, which are graded pretty average, not hard, but not easy. There is 1 midterm and 1 final. They are pretty easy, mostly remembering what was talked about in class. I gained a lot from this course, and Brother Woodward made all the D&C sections make sense.

Brother Woodward really cares about his students' learning, and is always willing to give great amounts of help. Be sure to at least do the historical background and section reading before class. FOLLOW THE GRADING CRITERIA. He looks for very specific things, especially in the papers. It's pretty easy to lose points on essays.

Brother Woodward is a great teacher. He puts the Doctrine and Covenants into a historical context that adds to the meaning of each section. If you keep up on the assignments, do the study guide, and attend the reviews the tests are easy. He grades his papers hard, but I learned a lot from writing them.

Bro Woodward is a funny guy and a good lecturer. His assignments really help you understand what you are reading. However, his tests are hard and oddly specific, much like other religion professors at BYU. Make sure you memorize dates and every little detail contained in the reading and lectures.

Brother Woodward is AWESOME. First day of classes i sat in on his class to see if i wanted in, and was moved during his lecture. He is incredible, cares about his students, and helps you really learn the material. Tests require lots of studying, but i thought it was worth while! Would definitely take again.

Woodward was a fantastic professor. I am taking another class from him because he was so helpful and his lectures were engaging, funny, and very informative. Woodward has extensive knowledge of the Doctrine and Covenants as well as a lot of other church material! I would strongly recommend taking a class from Woodward.

Two papers,  D&C section summaries and attendance in class. Professor Woodward is very knowledgeable with lots of supplemental material on his website. All of the work actually helps you learn which makes it worth it. Also, HE IS HILARIOUS and class is never boring!!! I definitely recommend taking it from Professor Woodward!

I love Brother Woodward! There is reading required before each class and a section summary, but it isn't too bad.  He has 2 papers and just one test and a final.  He is really fair but his tests are a little hard to study for. You have to memorize what happens for each section. The final was really easy.  I think I got an A minus.

He's very knowledgeable and provides great resources. Also good at presenting an atmosphere of the Spirit. Furthermore, I had him when it was his first semester teaching but you really wouldn't have known. My only complaint is that the 2 tests and the 2 papers are ridiculous.

I took Dr. Woodward during his first semester teaching here at BYU. I was impressed by his knowledge and sources on the subject matter. I learned many new things and I definitely grew to understand and love Doctrine and Covenants more, which I think is the real purpose of this class anyway.
The material is great and Brother Woodward is very engaging in class. I loved going to class.

Brother Woodward is a FANTASTIC teacher. His lectures are very detailed and easy to understand. He also knows how to find humor in everything. I was unsure about his class at the beginning of the semester because it was his first semester at BYU, but boy am I glad I took his class. Learned a ton and really enjoyed the Doctrine and Covenants.

Brother Woodward is hilarious! He makes learning about Doctrine and Covenants easier, because he makes it fun. He is very willing to help students understand clearly what is going on in the different sections and has some really good resources for students as well. You do quite a bit of reading, but it is worth it.

He really knows his stuff! Great at answering difficult questions about church history! I learned so much and actually appreciate D&C now!!  His tests were difficult for a religion class. I got an A, but had to study way more than for any other religion class. It was his first semester and I think he is making it easier. SO nice. SO understanding.
His humble nature and his incredible knowledge of D&C lets the spirit help you learn things you have not seen before. He is amazing!...

Woodward definitely knows his Church History . Readings due every class - the sections and some background commentary on the sections. Attendance is recorded. He covers what's on the tests while in class - just take notes on the big things he says. Test came right from lecture material. You also have 2 papers in the semester -normal for a D&C class

I think Bro. Woodward is great. His teaching style is the best! He challenges the cultural beliefs of the church and teaches what the doctrine says. I love it. I'm taking  the second half of D&C from him next semester. My only problem is that my grade doesn't represent the amount I learned. He's a really tough grader and getting an A can be tough.

I really liked Brother Woodward. It was obvious that he cared a lot about the subject matter and his students. I learned a lot this semester and would definitely recommend him. Not too much work either!

I really enjoyed Brother Woodward's D&C class.  He is very clear about his expectations, and respectful to student views.  He's more than willing to help students understand material.  His section summaries may seem tedious at first, but they help you in the long run for exams.
Presents his own opinion on the subject as fact and uses controversial sources and accounts as if they were the the definitive answer in regards to whatever event he is presenting.

Brother Woodward is awesome. His lectures are incredibly informative, and yet he is still hilarious. I don't know how he does it but he can make the class funny yet a powerfully spiritual experience. You do have to read, but he gives backgrounds which help you understand the content of the scriptures. Went in for help on a paper and he was helpful.

This is one of the best classes I've ever taken, from one of the best instructors that I've ever had. Professor Benson is a phenomenal teacher. He applies everything we've learned to real-life scenarios that make it so easy to then use in the real world.

This class was super easy, a little test heavy but other than that you really only have a big group project. The assignments for the class are worth a pretty decent chunk but he has walkthroughs for all of them so you really don't need to put in that much effort to do well. As long as you do decent on the final and midterm it is an easy A/A-.
ratingTags: Accessible outside class--Graded by few things--Test heavy

comment: I really enjoyed Professor Benson's classes and felt like he prepares you for what is on the exams -you just have to put in the time to ensure you understand the concepts and know how to do the problems. He's a great guy outside the classroom as well. Would recommend!

To be honest I had to do several double takes when I saw all of these exceptional reviews. Benson is well-intentioned but the class is one of the most pointless classes I've taken. Most of the material is a review from Econ 110 or other low-level business classes. I would not recommend Benson, the lectures were dry and not engaging.

Professor Benson is very smart. The class is interesting but slow. The final project accounts for a major portion of the grade-- he will tell you what he wants and give you feedback. When you do what he wants and follow the feedback, it is not reflected in his grading. Class average was high so he had to lower the average by lowering project grades
ratingTags: Tough Grader--TEST HEAVY--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: He's a great teacher, especially for those with no background in econ or calculus. Very good at explaining. Just be prepared to really study for the exams, and there is a group project involved. I didn't need the textbook.

Professor Benson is probably the best professor I've had at BYU so far. He is great at explaining hard concepts in a way that I could understand. He took a fairly boring subject and made it fun. His class was easily one of my favorites this semester.

Dr. Benson is very intentional in his lecture topics and assignments. His courses are challenging but very reasonable, applicable to the real world and prepares students for their careers. He expects students to show up, participate, and give an honest effort but definitely rewards students that do so. I recommend him for any course he teaches!
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Clear grading criteria--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: Professor Benson is one of my favorite professors I've had.  His lectures were clear, useful, and memorable.  He gave great feedback that helped us learn solid skills and also discover new talents.   He also really cares about his students.  Professor Benson took the time to talk to me about the strategy program and help me apply.  Great professor!

Professor Benson is great at helping you find real life application for the content. It was definitely easier than expected which was nice. I think I heard econ and assumed more calc than we did which was scary, but it was a totally doable class. The lectures were engaging and I wanted to go to class.

Super great class and professor (and I didn't have a good experience in Econ 110). Even though he doesn't take attendance, he does a lot of in-class exercises which really help you learn, so I highly recommend that you attend class.  Also, his lectures are really interesting (much better than the book).
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Hilarious

comment: One of my favorite professors at BYU!  He really takes the time to make sure everyone can understand the material. I also loved all the real world examples he used in class.

I really enjoyed taking Strategy and Econ from Benson. He has a hilarious personality which helped me to stay engaged in class but also a love for what he teaches and it shows. I was worried about this class before taking it, because my experience with Econ 110 was not great. But I learned so much in this class that I know will be applicable.

Possibly my favorite class/professor of my BYU experience. Easy A. He is so really makes class interesting & fun. Basically no homework too. The big group project is a bit challenging depending on what company you get, but honestly, the midterm and non-cumulative final determine your grade since most get close to the same grade on everything else.

Pro. Benson is great is a teacher not a boring lecturer. He wants you to understand and get a good grade. Class is taught well and he gives a manageable amount of work. You should still probably go to class because the concepts aren't simple but his lectures are interesting and time usually passes fast. Take him even if you don't know econ/calc.

Dr. Benson was easily the best professor I had my last semester. His lectures and assignments were always super relevant, I never felt like I was just doing busy work. He is also very willing to meet with students, I ended up spending several hours in his office over the course of the semester to get help. Not even my major and I loved his class.

Dr. Benson is willing to go the extra mile for you. If you are willing to step up then you can count on him to be a great support and you will do great in his class. Great understanding of business outside the classroom. Great instruction in both lectures and from his office. He'll give you what you need to be successful In his courses.
This is a fairly easy class, but still useful to understand business strategy.

Professor Benson's lectures were interesting, engaging & current. He encouraged class discussion and shared stories & insight from his time in the field. We had two group projects which required us to apply what we learned to current industries/companies. Professor Benson was available for help & advice.  This was a great class - take it!  :)

If you have a chance to take a class from Dr. Benson, do it!  Dr. Benson doesn't just care about you when you are a student, but he is willing to help you in any way possible to be successful after his class.  His lectures are amazing, and I loved the cases we analyzed in his class as well.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Amazing lectures

comment: Very kind and brilliant professor! He is extremely knowledgeable about not only his subject matter but also the business world. If you reach out to him, he really takes the extra mile to help you in any way possible. Not gonna lie his tests are hard but then again the subject his hard.

Tyler was a fairly nice teacher. He wasn't the best at teaching cuz it was his first time teaching, but he was lenient and nice. He let you correct your exams and get half credit for everything you fixed. There were extra credit opportunities. I was usually lost in class and didn't understand what was going on, but I still did fine in the class.
He's great! If you're not satisfied with your grade, he'll basically give you things to do for extra credit until you have an A. Gives great feedback on everything

I flipping love Ben! His class was so fun. He genuinely cares about his students and you can definitely get a good grade in his class if you work for it. Three essays, which he grades fairly, and a final group project. Ben is hilarious, and each and every class period had a great convo going. Take him for your GE freshman course!

Professor Hill  She is really good teacher. I just felt at the end when i wasn't doing as good as maybe some of the others where she focused more on them. Sometimes she goes to fast over an idea and if you understand things slower you are caught playing catch up. Willing to help understand a principle as long as it doesn't interfere with her plans

She has a great relationship with her students: she told us to call her Krystal, she tried to learn everyone's names quickly, and wants so badly to help that she nearly begs us to come to math lab.  She is very enthusiastic and knows what she's doing, but oftentimes struggles to explain complicated concepts and ideas as to be understood easily.
The TA taught most of the class and was heavily relied on. It was a fine class, Chinese is hard. The teacher seemed to know a lot about Chinese culture and was often trying to prove it.
ratingTags: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Dr. Heath is an a great professor who cares about his students and want them to perform well in his class. He's super passionate about Chinese and his students. He also tries to make his lectures as enjoyable and interactive as possible.

Class is difficult just because Chinese is difficult. But seriously, I'm pretty sure most of mine received an A. He's a good professor and knows what he is talking about. Just make sure you prepare and come on time. But to be completely honest, your experience largely depends on who the TA is because they teach most of the class.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Caring--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: Dr. Heath's class wasn't super well organized (might have been his first semester teaching CHIN 102), and it wasn't too easy, either. But, as a professor, he was great. He really cared about the class; at the end of the year we had a Christmas party together, earlier in the year we went out for Chinese food. And he makes learning Chinese fun.
Great teacher. Makes learning Chinese interesting and fun.
Will lecture you for being late to class. Doesn't connect well with students. Frequently posts assignments the day they are due. Doesn't prepare you for the test. Take this class from someone else.
Knows a lot about the Chinese language and culture.

Kalyn is great! Really easy-going and understanding, plus she loves giving extra credit, and is always trying to improve her teaching methods - she regularly asked for and listened to our feedback. The tests were pretty difficult, but that's the department's fault, and her review powerpoints always helped - especially the one for the final.

Kalyn is awesome and is a great teacher. They discourage the language teachers from speaking in English, so Kalyn would act out words and draw little things to help you rememberunderstand words. We also had in-class reviews before the tests which were extremely helpful. Fantastisch Lehrerin!

Kalyn is great. She's super funny and the most helpful teacher I've had at BYU so far. She's easy to work with and helps you to succeed. She will be there when ever you need her. She really gives it her all and tries to make sure everyone is doing well. I would definitely take more classes from her. She's like a friend who helps you to learn.

Funny class! She acts lots of things out to try to get the class to understand without using English. If you need help, just ask and she will help you one on one. Can be a tough grader for the things already taught. Takes time to review and go over common mistakes. She seems to like giving extra credit.
Class really wasn't that hard with him. Didn't have much homework, and midterm was easy. He gives all the questions to the Final before hand as well.

I don't think STATs is as hard as he is making it. He reads off the slides and then sometimes doesn't even understand what he is reading.  No explanations of how to solve things.  He gets lost in it himself and doesn't answer questions in a clear manner. Do not take STATS from him.

This was not a fun class for me. I'm good at math, but this class was confusing and I ended up using the textbook to teach myself more than I ever have in any class. Also Professor Snow really likes elephant jokes. It gets old quickly.
A pretty good teacher, but he tends to ramble.

Tech1010 from him was super easy. He doesn't force participation or require attendance, which actually made some of his more involving lessons more interesting. Most of the time I sat quietly in the back and he was OK with that.
This class is super easy. Just do the assignments on Canvas and you'll pass without a problem.
ratingTags: Clear grading criteria--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--EXTRA CREDIT

comment: Professor Zsiros is extrememly easy going. The class (MFG 130) is an intro class, and his saying about once a week was, well if it gets you interested in it and you kind of know what we're talking about then we've done our job. Great guy, willing to help out. Not sure how he'd be with any other course. Labs are fun and easy, just show up for them.

Dr. Brooks is eloquent, intelligent, respectful, experienced, and often funny. His class was orderly and interesting. Two midterms; one literature review due at the end of the semester. TA reviews were very helpful. Visiting the county jail was the highlight of the course for me. His stories were relevant to course material and funny.

Mike is hilarious, very fair, and a good teacher. The course is easy - show up, take notes, GO TO THE TA REVIEW and you'll do great. Mike makes it really interesting and fun and he's got a lot to say. Great class. Take it from him.

He knows his stuff and is well respected/well known at BYU, but I feel like he talked through most of our lessons rather than getting to the point. I didn't improve as much as I could have or should have. He also picked strange songs and fixated on them, and if I'm not passionate about what I'm singing, it becomes a chore to practice.
Great voice teacher! Explains things on a level that you can understand, and encourages you all the way through the learning process.
Great teacher. I recommend this class to anyone. Riley is really helpful, kind, and generous. She's the ideal teaching assistant.

Professor Bassett was one of the best english teachers I've ever had.  She's a grad student so she's really friendly, approachable and always willing to help you if you need it.  If you put the time in to make sure that your essay follows the rubric she gives you, you can get an A.  One of my favorite college classes yet.

Riley was an awesome teacher. She makes class super fun and interesting. There are a few reading assignments and the essays aren't too bad. Riley gives good feedback and suggestions and lets you revise your papers before the semester ends.

Riley was a great teacher! I have always hated writing, but she made class interesting and was very helpful with assignments. She lets you redo any essay that you received a bad grade on. She is also willing to look at your drafts and edit them, which helps a ton. I actually loved her class, even though I hate writing.
