Really awesome class, knows  greek and hebrew and brings some great insights to the new testament
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria

comment: This class is straight lectures. He certainly knows the material and has some good insights, but he is not very good at engaging the class with questions. His questions are very leading to specific answers that no one seems to get right. There is very little wiggle room for your grade, you mess up once and you're in a tight place for the semester.
Good class, Everything is fair and transparent. He helped me when I did not do well on the first exam and took time outside his normal office hours. I would recommend the class.

Professor Shafer was great, she's really good about making sure everyone understands a concept before she moves on. She goes above and beyond the department requirements to make sure you feel confident about your signing abilities. Her tests aren't too hard as long as you study the vocab.
Lauren is a great professor! She

Lauren is the BEST. She's fun and hilarious. Made me love ASl. This was one of my highest grades, because she's a fair grader, and I actually wanted to do the work, because it was enjoyable! Do the required reading and homework. Do NOT put off labs, clubs, and CLL or you will be in deep soup. Enjoy!

Lauren is AMAZING. Seriously! ASL 101 was by far my FAVORITE class this semester.  Lauren is great at explaining any sign or concept not immediately understood. She is hearing and therefore gets when we may have trouble comprehending. Read the chapters for DCA Quizzes. Don't delay Labs/Club/CLL. Do ALL of your homework. My love for ASL grew!!

Lauren was my favorite professor this semester. TAKE HER CLASS. Seriously, it was my favorite and I looked forward to it everyday. My love for ASL grew because of Lauren. She knows how to connect with students and keeps the class light and fun. I cannot say enough how much I loved this class and Lauren!

She's hearing, so she knows how to explain why certain signs are the way they are.  Whereas a deaf teacher wouldn't.  She's funny and loves her students.  She's young and just graduated so she understands the workload we already have.  She's honestly one of my good friends.

Lauren was incredible! We got to know her as a friend as well as a teacher and she was funny, sweet and helpful. She was clear and good about making sure we understood. Read up for the DCA quizzes! I took notes and that really helped me get 100% on almost all of them. Don't procrastinate your CLLsclubslabs! I fell in love with ASL in this class!

This is my 6th semester at BYU and Lauren has by far been one of my all time favorite teachers. Initially,  I was terrified to be completely immersed in ASL right away since I had zero experience with it, but Lauren totally understands where we're at and makes the class easy to follow along with and fun. Looked forward to it every day. Take her.

Lauren is one of the best teachers I had this term, she knows how to teach ASL and loves it too. If someone doesn't understand  the information she explains it in a different way. She's there to help you both in and out of class and truly cares for you as an individual person.

Lauren is the best! I loved this class. It wasn't too difficult; Lauren is very clear and makes sure everybody understands everything before moving on. The HW was easy and helpful! Definitely no busy work, it all helped us learn and understand ASL better. This is a great class. P.S. Lauren is a FANTASTIC dancer.
Best 101 teacher ever!!! Helps you understand. You need to pay attention and take notes. Make are you study hard for DCA tests and you will do great. :)

Lauren is the best! She cares about her students, and we all ended up being good friends with her. There is reading every once in a while and quizzes on that but if you just read the chapter it's not bad. the hw is actually really easy, only takes a couple of minutes a day. Definitely my favorite class this term, and will miss it. Great environment

This class was so much fun. Lauren is a hearing ASL teacher, and she barely just graduated. I was in her first ASL class here at BYU. She so helpful, and the tests are easy. As long as you pay attention, this class can be a breeze. I've heard from other ASL 101 students that their teachers aren't too great, but Lauren is amazing.

Lauren is an awesome ASL teacher. She goes over all the vocab multiple times. Make sure to write them all down with helpful hints of how to remember the words. The tests aren't hard, and there's a few quizzes over readings. Read the chapter, and you'll be fine. There are many other teachers for this course, but I would take Lauren again no question

Best teacher I had at BYU, hands down.  He's an easy grader but somehow makes all the students very interested in the material at the same time.  He avoids involving mormonism in the lectures as much as he can, which is refreshing for byu.

I did more homework for this class than all my other classes put together. Seriously. However, I learned way more in this class than all my other classes put together times 15. This class is worth the time. I don't ever do readings for classes, but I did all the readings for this class and it was worth it!

This class is a great class! I love the format and style of the discussions. Although there was a lot of reading, the works we read this semester were amazing and I felt that I learned a lot about Japan and life from the readings.  Also, I love Dr. Gessel. It was a miracle that I was able to take his class and I learned so much. I can't even expres
Always clear, always willing to work with you!

Mrs Schneck is one of the most helpful teachers I've had at college. She's not always completely clear on what she expects, but if you care about your grade and go to her she's definitely willing to help. If you wanna make an A, you can if you try hard enough, but it does take effort. She can tell when you spent time on essays. Go to writing lab!

Be ready to write a lot. It is a class that really helped me learn to write well but sometimes I got grades on essays I didn't agree with. She lets you rewrite some of the essays though if you got a bad grade. Be ready to dedicate a lot of time to this class.

Sister Schneck is one of the best teachers I have ever had. She is so willing to work with you and help you improve your writing. She really enjoys watching her students grow. I would definitely recommend her to anyone. You're going to have to work (it's Writing 150. You're going to write) but she will make it worth your time.

Gina Schneck is an amazing teacher! She gives great feedback on your essays and allows rewrites. She cares more about you learning how to write than grades. She's really passionate about what she does.

Dr. Culatta is such a nice lady, but her classes are hard to go to. She knows what she is talking about but it feels very slow placed. Hard to stay focused, but she loves what she is talking about. Projects aren't too bad, do them in a group. The tests can be a little unclear so go to the TA reviews before!

Ok, so this class is required anyways. Project started out confusing but in the end saved my grade. READ I can't stress that enough, and make outlines of the readings and lectures together. The class was hard, but everyone sucked so it curved and I got an A+ which I thought was a miracle.

Dr. Cullatta is really nice but I really did not enjoy her class or her teaching style. She reads right from the slides and often seems disoriented and loses her train of thought. She is not clear what she expect students to know for exams (there is a LOT of information). In fact, the exams are obscure and confusing. There are not a lot of points.

I really liked this class, but there were only 10 students.  I did really well on the tests and enjoyed Dr. Culatta's teaching style (I know this isn't true for all students in my class).  She does read off of powerpoints a lot, but when she's not doing that, the activities are helpful.  Be prepared to study for tests - they're 75% of your grade.

Steve is a grad student but still knows how to teach. He is willing to fight for the grade of the students. He teaches and lectures well, however he can lose his patience when he has to repeat his self, various times over the same topic. The online homework is annoying, though.

Steve is a fun lecturer who engages you in the subject of that day. He is very easy to talk to when you have questions about the homework and test. As long as you stay on top of the homework and go to his reviews during lecture and class, your grade will be fine.

Steve is a great and exciting teacher to be around. He is very helpful when you need him and he wants everyone to get an A. He wants to teach the most helpful topics of math so that you can succeed in upper level classes.
Clear, willing to help, very smart, relates well with students.
Really good at explaining concepts on a one-on -one basis. Very approachable.

You have to understand that this is a Calculus 2 class. Of course it's going to be difficult! But he really does do the best he can to help you understand. Incredibly willing to change teaching strategies for your personal benefit. Overall great TA. Best math TA I have had yet in my three courses here. Always willing to help as long as it takes.

Very good TA. He loves pure math, and although he skips some "easy" algebra if you ask him to go over it he will. Go into his office hours and he will help you with questions and go through step by step.

He is very passionate about pure math which leads him to be very thorough. He explains concept in multiple ways to help all students understand. He also is very good about covering the entire topic so the big picture is clear.  Also has an engaging teaching style so that classes aren't too boring.

He was ridiculous about grading specific notations. The first time I went to him for help he was extremely helpful and walked me step by step on the problem I needed help on. The next time he completely rushed through the elementary algebra and wouldn't help me understand conceptual ideas, and just told me to "take it for granted".
Awesome guy who is really good at math. This is his one downfall because he has to tone it down for his students to follow his work. Nonetheless a good teacher and is ultimately really helpful.
Nice guy... Really intense about notation and little insignificant math things. Likes to use really hard problems for practice in class. But he knows his stuff and helps you understand.

Gordon Mower is my favorite philosophy professor so far. I am literally trying to take him for everything left in my major possible. This is the philosophy classes I have learned most from thus far. Instead of learning only how to write philosophy and looking over ideas and trying to re-express them, this class really plants them in your mind.

Phil 202 is a great option to get your Letters and Civ II GE's! Dr. Mower is a really chill professor who loves giving out extra credit and little homework. Four 500-750 word response papers, one 2000 word term paper, and a midterm and final where he gives you the questions beforehand. Only gripe is that he easily got off topic in his lectures.

Dr. Mower is an awesome teacher. The tests are increeedibly fair and easy to do well on if you just take the time to study. He's the perfect example that a course doesn't need to be very difficult to be very informative. I've taken a lot of classes at BYU and he's about the only professor I'd recommend without reservation.

Do not let any of the negative reviews deter you from taking a class from Dr. Mower. He is a fantastic teacher and is one the most brilliant men I know. All the non-philosophy majors who take his class have no how lucky they are to have such a great professor. If you are an philosophy major, try to take as many of his classes as possible.
Dr. Mower is a FANTASTIC teacher. Try to take a class from him every semester, you will not regret it. He is brilliant, get ready to learn!!!

201 & 202 are ran the same way. Mower is a funny guy, his lectures can get boring cause Philosophy. In class quizzes, but he normally warns you and gives you all the info you need. 2 tests with reviews that make it super easy. 3 papers (last one incorporates previous 2). Some reading required, I hardly did any. Mostly lecture videos for homework.
ratingTags: BEWARE OF POP QUIZZES--Clear grading criteria--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: You could tell he knew his stuff, but he wasn't that great about sharing that knowledge with the students. He was often confusing, and the semester schedule was SO disorganized. I like knowing whats going on, but he was constantly changing dates for papers, tests, and quizzes, and so it was hard to schedule your time efficiently.

Here's the thing, if you're at college to actually become educated, take Mower.  If you don't want to try, don't.  He's easily one of the most well-qualified professors on campus, very intelligent.  He's got a great sarcastic sense of humor. Had him for 1st half of Wester Philosophy too, loved it. He wants good essays and usually gives easy tests.

Professor Mower is a great man.  If I wasn't in his class I would absolutely love carrying on discussions with him.  However, his class is the most challenging class I have taken in my BYU career.  The tests were based on tricking you rather than teaching you.  Hopefully his class will get better, but I would recommend anyone run from this class.
Really fun guy and tries to make class interesting. He will add cultural and historical viewpoints to the lecture. Also I actually took 102

Gwyn totally rocks - he made every class worth attending, both covering the material and keeping it interesting. The course was organized by the department, so even when things were crazy, it wasn't his fault and he did his best to make things work. He listens to commentsconcerns from students and is overall just a cool guy and good teacher.

Gwyn is a great teacher, he does his best to be clear, and he helps with the tests as best as he is able to in giving partial credit if you had the right idea, but misspelled a word. He does also offer a fair bit of extra credit, so if you participate and work hard, you can get extra credit which can have a big impact.
had a great time in that class
Gwyn is awesome and does what he can. When I took this class the grading was all weird and terrible, but that was the department who decided that, not Gwyn.

Your language skills will grow hugely in this class, and the assignments are a lot of fun. Get ready to hunker down and do a lot of work--there is a lot of writing, memorization, and speaking involved. But Gwyn is approachable, very helpful both in and out of class, and can actually comment on German culture, being from Frankfurt.

Gwyn's a good teacher. He's a native german speaker, which means he's great for learning vocabulary, but he can't  explain the grammar very well to non-native speakers. The course is assignment heavy. Clear your schedule for this class; it's time consuming. All the learning is online, and we review in class.

The course is a trial and so that was pretty difficult, but don't hold that against him. Gwyn is an awesome guy and a lot of fun to learn from. He wants you to learn and will take your suggestions. He's a really funny guy.

Sometimes it feels like a lot of assignments because you're always writing and correcting journal entries then taking quizzes, but I could really see my German improving over this semester. The course itself needs a little work, but the teacher's pretty cool.

He's a good teacher, pretty fair, although he is kinda limited in what he can do because of the online coursework, and the fact that he only grades a few of the assignments. I prefer his grading over pretty much all of the others.

Gwyn is a far better teacher than the class. The class has a horrible format (flipped teaching) but they're slowly improving it. Gwyn is personable and speaks fluent German. Fun teacher to have, enjoyed having him. Gwyn will help if you really need it. Go to the consultation center for all your papers and stay on top of the quizzes. Take his class!

Gwyn is pretty great! I enjoyed his perspective and teaching style, as well as the opportunity to participate in class. The course was arranged oddly, but that wasn't his fault. He made it bearable and fun!

The class has a lot of things to work through as of 2014. But, Gwyn is REALLY good at German. He knows his stuff and what is right and wrong. If you want to become better with a native, take it with him!
He is a native and therefore makes less mistakes then other Student Instructors. But he can't always explain the grammar.

She held individual writing conferences with each student before an essay was due where you could ask questions, get help with essay structure, or really anything that had to do with your essay.  If something was unclear, she was always willing to help and make herself accessible.  I really enjoyed her class.  It was small and more personable.
She's a pretty tough grader on all of the essays. Sometimes unfair, really. She's not that great at explain things so I would recommend taking this class from someone else!

I think his teaching in the class is great. Very insightful, uses gospel concepts while teaching about art, and also applies it to real world careers. But his grading is extremely harsh. Tiny things will get docked points. I think it's pretty difficult to please him. It's a shame because I love his personality but this class gave me so much stress!

Professor Dibble is a great painter, but not so great a great teacher. He seems to think that the whole world revolves around his class. I spent 3 times more time on his class only to get a below average grade.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Skip class? You won't pass.--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: Brother Dibble Takes his work seriously and expects you to do the same. I have never been pushed so hard in my life! I absolutely appreciated it no matter how stressful it got (and it did get stressful) His classes are very organized  and his expectations are clear: professionalism. If you're up for the challenge, expect to improve exponentially!

He is very good at explaining new concepts. He creates a very low-stress learning environment. Easy to ask questions in class. He's super entertaining in his lectures. I didn't attend class for 4 weeks and I did just fine.

Chris was hilarious. I feel like he really helped me improve as a singer. He wasn't always super clear on what he wanted you to do and got frustrated occasionally. But he did try and he did fairly well for a graduate student. The class was easy; show up and you basically have an A.
One of the best choral directors I've had. He made class fun and entertaining while using his contagiously good attitude toward music to inspire and direct the class.

Downard is a babe and a funny guy.  He defiantly knows his material but sometimes has a hard time expressing what he expects from you. He also is slightly forgetful but he is a graduate student so he is VERY understanding. The tests, or his expectations for your performance, are on the harder and higher side. Have time to devote to this class.

Boyack is the overseer of cello lessons. You will actually take lessons from a graduate student. I had Joseph Woodward as my instructor and he is amazing. Joseph has been playing the cello for year and is very helpful. He is also very patient and emphasizes the basics of the instrument so you have great form. I would highly recommend these lessons.

As long as you do the assignments he gives, you'll get an A, but I'm pretty sure he requires more drafts of the standard writing assignments than other teachers. There's no tests, and your final is an easy take-home  packet. His weekly required office visits can be a pain to remember, but they're super helpful if you have questions.

Killgore is the best. He is very tough when it comes to how many papers you write and you also have to do office visits every week but I learned so much from him. You write more papers than other teachers and in less time but he helps when you need him to. TAKE WRTG 150 FROM HIM!!  You start out as a bad writer but usually end with an A with work.
Tara is a great professor! Her lectures are clear and easy to understand and the tests are a breeze!
She is a wonderful professor who is very easy to approach. The class is pretty simple, but she makes it fun!

Tara is an amazing teacher. You have to go to classes since it's a lab, but she grades mostly on participation and is always willing to help give advice. The only parts where you're most likely to miss points are the three quizzes and the final.

Though he has great intentions, the way that Anand teaches is a bit scatter-brained and hard to follow. Most of the time, I just ended up reading the book to get the info that I needed. He is willing to help if you go in and talk with him, but I never had time that coincided with his office hours. I would recommend taking from another for clarity.
Pretty chill class.

I feel bad giving Brother Hillery this low of a score for his first review, especially since this was his first time teaching, but it is what it is. I really enjoyed the material in this class, but lectures were consistently boring and confusing. Tests were curved ridiculously up to make up for the fact that most of the class didn't learn anything.

Feel like I didn't learn a whole lot. He was very hands-off and it was hard to tell which parts of the lecture were super important and which were just FYI. It's completely group-based, so pick a group you like. Would recommend for the experience and resume booster of working with real clients.
LOVED this class. So much actionable instruction. Very hands on (we managed social media accounts for real companies). Would highly recommend!

I love Brandon. He actually started and currently runs a digital media company, so he knows his stuff. You have a find a real client to run their social media for the semester, but that's all your homework. Easy class, I learned a lot, and Brandon can give you some great connections. You don't have to go to class, but you'll miss out if you don't.
Cool class. Lots of group work on projects for real clients. Learned a ton about social mediadigital strategy.

Prof. Ariizumi is great if you want to learn Japanese! Not so much if you just want the class credit, though. He gets you to read and study a lot. For his class in particular, the less proficient you are in Japanese, the more difficult the course will be. Still, he's kind, wants the best for his students, and is willing to work with you if you ask.

Granted, the class was not well organized.  A clear syllabus of what assignments and quizzes would happen when would have been very helpful.  While I studied a lot of kanji, I learned a lot from this class (and 321)!  The negative students here are just bitter - Ariizumi Sensei is very nice, sincere, and understanding, even if he is disorganized.

Unreasonable work load. Assigns 200 kanji at a time and only fifteen appear on quizzes. Very poorly organized class and he is unapologetic about it. Shows up late to class and asks everyone else to be on time. Too much busy work. Did not like Japanese as much as I used to after his class.

Really good man. You can tell he genuinely wants you to learn Japanese, but I get the sense that he thinks his is the only class students take. He treats a 3 credit course like a 6 credit course, so buckle up and prepare to spend many hours every week reading articles that you don't care about. He is understanding about absences, which is awesome.

He really enjoys interaction with students and wants to be a help in students' lives.  His teaching is good, even if the semester is slightly disorganized. The focus is on chigen-iku, which is like his own version of habits for highly effective people.

Ariizumi has a very interesting approach to teaching. He does not necessarily teach Japanese as a language, but he uses his classes as a vehicle to teach you how to study and how to improve. He wants you to improve in Japanese, but his main concern is that his students turn out as great people. His class is disorganized and random, but I loved it.

While there is definitely a chance he will improve (he hasn't been at BYU very long) I would not recommend the class. Ariizumi-sensei's class was fairly unorganized and probably much more demanding than if you took it from another teacher. Kanji quizzes could include entire phrases or random words such as "retina."

Julie is one of the BEST professors. She is so kind, caring, and has a lot of experience to learn from! Her lectures are sometimes a little long, but I learned so much in this class about being a true professional. Just keep up on the assignments and attend the TA review sessions, and you'll do great!

Dr. Lemon has an interesting way of running his class. Instead of teaching us any material at all, he allows groups of 2-3 people to choose certain topics from various subjects in the book to present in the front of class. Every group will do about 10 presentations. Final is only worth 10% of the final grade, and homework is just reading/questions.
It is a lot of work; the TA kind of took over the class, and so you don't have some of the usual Lemon easiness.

Not clear at all in our assignments and what is graded. Group presentations every week. Just started using a new textbook on Tophat which has huge chapters and tons of vague questions not answered in the text (and you have to read multiple chapters for each class period). Very time consuming busywork, not enjoyable, and not a good way to learn.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--LOTS OF HOMEWORK--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: Pretty chill class, learned a lot of vocab and grammar for medical situations! Class is a very easy A but attendance is mandatory. Mostly group presentations which are easy but get really boring after a while. 2 tests that are online and you can take them as many times as you want.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--Clear grading criteria

comment: Dr. Lemon has been one of my favorite teachers. His class is super easy and very beneficial for those who want to learn more of the medical spanish world. Super enjoyable. easy A

It's an easy class, and you get out what you put in.  If you don't pay attention, you won't learn much but your grade won't suffer for it.  He uses group presentations as the majority of the class period, but they're short and to the point.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Skip class? You won't pass.--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: I enjoyed the class but found it rather frustrating a lot of the time because of how it was organized. I felt like we were trying to learn way too much complicated stuff in a very short amount of time. Lots of student presentations, which can end up pretty boring. Not a hard class in the end though.

This class was exactly what I wanted!  I speak Spanish and plan on a medical career and I think that this class helped integrate the two perfectly.  We do presentations, but they aren't too difficult and really help to understand the material better.  All in all a very good class!
Great Professor. I recommend taking him.  He is highly knowledgeable.   I have no complaints.
Dr. Lemon is a nice guy but I feel like his expectations we not the clearest. I really enjoy the material but I feel like there is a lot lacking in the organization of the class.

Dr. Lemon is a Former ER practitioner with a lot of experience so expect to learn lots of new medical terms in Spanish. Everyone say that its an easy A, and yeah it basically is, if you do the work. Weekly open notes and book quizzes and also online midterm and Final. Very interesting class. Medicine students MUST take this class.

Charles Lemon is a great teacher, highly recommended. He is very flexible in his grading and wants you to get an A. The bookwork can be a bit tedious but learn the basics of his class and you will get an easy A.

Dr. Lemon is great. Very clear, and is completely willing to help you succeed.  The class is a cinch- one paper, weekly LS quizzes, one midterm, and final (all open-book).  Attendance is a good chunk of your grade, so show up to class and participate in role-plays.  Easy class, but still learned a ton of useful stuff.

This is the easiest spanish class I have taken, but also one where I learned new grammar.  There are weekly online quizzes due that are cake, as well as one online midterm and online final.  All super easy and based off of quizzes.  Attendance required for grade.  Super easy A. Lemon is a great guy. Take this class!

Difficult, but super interesting class. Group project about scientific papers every week (useful for MCAT prep, but time consuming). Test questions are tricky/ambiguous, but usually doable. Most test material comes directly from the slides/notes he posts, which is nice. He's big on focusing on current research, which was interesting!

I honestly have never loved learning about biology on a cellular or molecular level. Nor did I understand many of the procedures and techniques used in these fields. Dr. Alder helped me to change that! He finds ways to involve students in a large classroom, he uses humor in his teaching, and his goal is to help students develop! Great guy!

Big focus on reading research papers in this class. We devote at least half our time to doing that. Dr. Alder is a nice guy, but Dr. Hill's lectures are a lot more organized, and I believe his tests tend to be a little less brutal as well. Dr. Alder really makes you work for your grade. There's a ton of material to memorize for tests.
ratingTags: Tough Grader--GRADED BY FEW THINGS--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: This was my favorite course at BYU.  Dr. Alder is an awesome teacher. He's hilarious and is very intelligent. The best thing about this class was that it taught me how to read scientific papers. We have one weekly and we work on them in groups. Tests are very specific, but if you memorize everything on the slides, you'll do fine.

Dr. Alder has a lot to offer: he is funny, sharp, and invested in the course. However, his lack of organization prevented him from conveying information effectively in a lecture setting. His style of teaching is choppy and disorienting, so it was hard to see how concepts connected, especially as there wasn't a course textbook.

He's not especially open to feedback in spite of preaching the importance of humility. Rushes through his slides so he can spend more time talking about research. Learning to read / interpret primary research is an important skill but he neglects other things to accomplish that. A lot of things he glosses over in lecture end up on the tests.
ratingTags: Skip class? You won't pass.--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: Dr alder is the first teacher I've had at byu that doesnt give me information to memorize but truly taught me how to think in a scientific context. the skills i learned by the paper sets he has us do are valuable. i would say that he is truly the smartest professor i have taken that truly thinks very originally. his tests are like the MCAT

He is a very nice guy and will take the time to talk to you outside of class if you need help. He taught us how to read papers, which has been very useful. However, his tests were extremely difficult for biology. Questions were obscure and tested your ability to take tests rather than your ability to understand the information.

I quite enjoyed Dr. Alder's class. It wasn't a particularly easy class, but neither was it extremely difficult. The weekly group projects were easy if you work well in groups, and beyond that there's no homework assignments or reading. The tests were somewhat tough, but his test style is extremely similar to the MCAT, for what it's worth

Doctor Alder is one of the best professors I have had. The way he sets up the class makes it easy to learn the material if you put in the time. He explains concepts really well in class, and the way he does his slides are extremely helpful. This class helped me become a better analyzer, critical thinker, and student.

Dr. Alder's rating is too low to accurately reflect how amazing this professor is. His class is hard, but it's one of the best things I've ever done since I've been in college. He treats his students with the utmost respect, and he pushes you to do hard things because he knows what you're capable of. Put in the time & effort and you won't regret it

Dr. Alder is a great guy, and you learn a lot in this class.  His notes on the powerpoints are useful.  His tests though could use some refinement - he leaves some holes in the logic required to get to the answer that he is thinking of -it's possible to get to an answer that's defensible but not in line with his thinking.  Good luck if that happens

Dr. Alder is a great guy, but this is a difficult class.  Pick a good group to score well on the problem sets. The only way to get help on the individual project is to talk to him or a TA, but nobody else can even be in the same room and he disallows any communication between students. Tests were surprisingly hard even when I felt I knew it all.

Dr. Alder really cares about his subject and wants you to be passionate about it too.  There's a scientific paper you have to read each week; just read the abstract and logic out the figures. Adds fantastic notes onto his slides for tests.  No textbook.  Make sure you get a good group, you'll work with them the whole semester.

Dr. Alder is awesome! In class, he really helps you to think creatively as a scientist instead of just regurgitating facts. However,  I felt like his approach to testing was very inconsistent with his teaching style- Two of the three tests (Dr Hansen wrote them) were full of very poorly worded questions.

I loved this class. No homework, technically - problem sets are due once a week, but they are group effort and one hour of class time a week is dedicated to completing the set. 2 midterms, multiple choice, not too hard but not easy. Definitely requires study. Dr. Alder is hilarious and there is a lot of class discussion.
Dr. Alder is very funny and approachable. Every person I know loves him as a teacher. Definitely would recommend you take this from him.
Best professor on campus. That is not an opinion. Funny, helpful, and he's really good-looking. He always has free M&M's in his office as well.
Honestly great teacher great class! Had a blast and he actually made writing fun
Scott is the man!! I would take his class every year if I could. He really wants you to succeed in the class.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--ACCESSIBLE OUTSIDE CLASS--Amazing lectures

comment: I loved this class. Scott knows what he's doing and he never wasted time on meaningless assignments. It seems that most of my friends' WRTG 150 classes required a lot of reading and busywork, but Scott keeps it simple and as easy as possible. He was also super helpful with one-on-one meetings and did a lot to help improve my writing.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Respected--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: Scott is an amazing human and even better professor. Gives great feedback, cares about his students' success, and willing to help. Very few assignments go into your grade, though, and most of them are papers.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Respected--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: He is a funny guy. Class isn't always super organized and can get off track, but he provides good feedback, is accessible, and covers the material. A few papers are the big grades of course, but he helps a  lot to write them well. Probably an easier option for a writing teacher, but you'll still learn.
Scottie P is an amazing teacher. I learned so much more about writing, and he made it easy. He gives awesome feedback and his lectures helps out a ton.
Lord Scott is the best. My WRTG 150 class was the easiest out of any of my friends. Do yourself a favor and take it from Scott.

Best teacher ever! I hate WRTG and this was my funnest class! Scott really knows what he is doing. I respect him as a teacher! He cares about his students. His lectures are never boring !!!! I cant say enough good about him!
No one deserves that chili pepper more than Scott. What a gem. Genuinely going to miss his class.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--CARES ABOUT STUDENTS--Respected by students

comment: Scott is an awesome Professor. He genuinely wants to help his students become better writers and will give any feedback you ask for. Class isn't mandatory, but his lectures are entertaining and helpful. I suggest taking him!

The only long paper was the 10 page research article, which we had a lot of prep time for. It took me a bit longer to do since I got sick for an entire week during the library unit (if you've ever seen groups of students "touring" the library, it's for this class.) Best teacher to take the WRTG 150 class from. No tests. Merciful in grading.

Scott is great. He doesn't believe in busy work, and he's very fair on grading. Long papers, but its a writing class, so its expected. If you are offended easily I wouldn't recommend taking it from him because his humor can be hit sensitive people the wrong way. Take writing 150 from him

He loves flattery and T. S. Eliot. Call him Lord Scott, or better yet, come up with something more creative, like Darth Scott or Fuhrer Scott.   In all seriousness, he's one of my favorite teachers and I had a great time in his class.

Scott is a very funny grad student. If you like witty teachers take his class. He always keeps lectures interesting and genuinely care for you. He has very good feedback on your papers and is willing to help if you ask. You can afford to miss some class.

Likes to be Addressed as Lord Scott. He is funny and a good teacher and cares about his students deep down inside. He takes quite awhile to put in grades though. But overall, I would definitely take a class from him again. He is a good guy.

Grad student. This was my second time taking the class, and Scott was amazing. Very friendly, knew the occasional BS in the system, really no busywork, and classes were always interesting and usually helpful, very often based on the next assignment and adapted to the class. Funny, too!! Pretty easy, as well.

Homework due once a week and it is a reasonable amount of homework for how much we learn. His tests are hard though, and you have to be able to understand what you are actually doing and how to take a problem one step farther. Is a generous grader though on tests, and also grades them really quickly. Overall, I would say he is alright

HW due every week, on Monday, which is good. Tests are hard, kind of hit-and-miss, often with a few proofs that are hard to understand. I hated the class but Prof. Zhao is OK, he was great about starting and ending class on time, pretty available, not too many questions in class though. Straight-laced but nice, and SUPER fast grader (and generous).

Unlandt is a great guy. Very funny and kind. His class is not very organized, however. The textbook required doesn't follow his lecture or tests - I barely read it. His lectures are long and can be tedious. Because the class is only graded by 2 tests and a group paper, 95% of the time the class is stress-free. 5% of the time it's a nightmare.
ratingTags: Accessible outside class--Graded by few things--Lecture heavy

comment: I like him. This class was much easier than I expected. He even let us work together on the final. He assigns almost no homework. His health isn't great so he had to cancel class a lot. Class was pretty much all lecture. He knows a lot about medieval literature and his lectures were interesting. He doesn't use learning suite.

Prof. Unlandt is probably the nicest and most understanding teacher I have ever had... but the class wasn't the best. He told us we have a paper due at the end of the semester but didn't give us information until a week before. There are only three grades in the class -- midterm, final, and the paper. Lectures are long.

This was a really hard subject for me but Prof Unlandt was always there to help. His relaxed demeanor is awesome. He is one of the nicest, most helpful professors I have ever had. I would love to take another class from him.

For any Dutch returned-missionaries, this class is fantastic. Tests are a breeze, and the 16-credit challenge exam is guaranteed A's. The Dutch history and literature portions are pretty interesting, the grammar and schrijfoefeningen are more dull. Super easy A and a lot of fun. Only offered in Fall semesters, though.
Tim is great at building relationships and showing you that he cares about helping you become the best CTRS out there. He teaches a lot about how to process and facilitate your own activities.
Great class to really get good real life therapy experience! Loved the class because everyone became very close. Still a lot of hard work

Andy treats you like an adult. Quizzes are based on group discussion. There is a final project but he gives you plenty of time and isn't a harsh grader. Go to class because there is a quiz every time. He is so connected and just wants to be a network for you. This class isn't hard, but you do learn a lot of applicable skills. He also brings pizza!

Andy is a fantastic professor, but get ready to work your butt off. No scrubs allowed here. You will work for that pizza. Lots of late nights with your group, and lots of time outside of class spent reading and writing. Andy gives good feedback and really wants you to succeed, but he expects you to give 100%.
ratingTags: LOTS OF HOMEWORK--SO MANY PAPERS--GROUP PROJECTS

comment: Andy is one of the best professors. He genuinely wants to help students and is willing to meet outside of class to talk about career plans, internships, etc. I never anticipated enjoying a research class this much. Make sure you get a dedicated group and you'll have a good semester. Our entire class was sad to leave on the last day!

Awesome awesome awesome. Genuine and gives helpful feedback. Really cares for his students and wants them to improve. Teaches material that I know I'll actually use in my life. Homework load is doable-- definitely do your reading. Ps. he brings pizza to class sometimes !!

Literally the best professor ever. Chill, helpful and knows so much about real life PR. This class helped me so much in applying the skills we're learning to the real world. He's young, funny, interesting to listen to, and on top of that he frequently buys pizza for the class. Doesn't get much better than that.
Goes above and beyond to help you succeed. Has a ton of real world experience. This class was well worth my time.

Andy is an outstanding instructor. The class is essentially a research project throughout the entire semester that revolves around a single company's problem. He has great experience and is there to help whenever you need it.  He also brings pizza to class because he gets hungry and he knows the students are too.

The class was a semester long research project for a local company. Andy has great insights of how companies work and tells you how things are. Really nice guy and wants you to succeed. Also his tangents are great, especially about Karate Kid.
Watson is the man. The way he looks out for, and cares for his students is unmatched.
Ordered Dominos pizza for the class twice and brought Krispy Kreme donuts. Then for the final he took us to Malawai's Pizza. Enough said!
Sitting here eating pizza he bought for the class. That says all you need to know.

Loves Karate kid, compliment his fast running, and tells funny embarrassing stories. Definitely a HOTT chili pepper.  But really, super chill and has fantastic real world experience and advice. Take it from him!
Loves Karate kid, compliment his fast running, and tells funny embarrassing stories. Definitely a HOTT chili pepper.  But really, super chill and has fantastic real world experience and advice.
AMAZING TEACHER!

He's the man! If you want real world experience from a professor who cares, then you should take this class from him. It's the only way that PR Research and Measurement will be understandable and interesting.

Andy is one of the best professors I have ever had at BYU. He really cares about his students and wants them to succeed. He also gives a lot of real world advice about how to get a job and improve your resume. I highly recommend taking a class from him, you won't regret it.
He is super unclear, and in order to pass this intro class, you pretty much have to a programming master already. Good luck.

Dr. Lund was a good professor. He gave quizzes in class graded on completion and was good at explaining the concepts. The TAs for this course are really what saves you. Do yCode and the labs on time and it's really fun. You'll learn so much.

Professor Choi is a great instructor. If you practice the pieces he tells you to, then you'll pass with an A. Be sure to attend ALL of your classes though. Attendance is a must since he's pretty hard to get to reschedule your time. He's very friendly and willing to help.

The lectures Sondrup give are straight off of Wikipedia. As 90% of this class is lecture-based with a midterm and a final to close it out, I would highly recommend not taking this class unless you need to. There are far better and more interesting professors in the Scandinavian department. As a teacher, I would not rate him very highly.
You needed to read and show up for class discussion, not because it was required in the grade (I believe), but because an understanding for the tests came from the reading and discussion

Professor Sondrup is a very nice, incredibly intelligent and very knowledgeable old man. But you should only take his class if you 1. Have nothing else going on in your life 2. You've read the texts before 3. You don't care about your grade andor 4. Your readingopinion of the texts is exactly the same as his reading. 25+ long, intense texts.

She's an awesome teacher. She uses lots of personal examples to explain concepts. You need to read the textbook. Daily reading quizzes.  About 80% of her test questions are super easy, and the other 20% just leave you wondering where the heck that information was. All in all, a good, fun class.

Professor Fetzer's class is really easy. I put in pretty minimal effort and got a pretty good grade. She was super nice and lenient for me on turning in an assignment late when I was stuck in a blizzard one weekend. Nothing is graded too difficult, but this was her first semester at BYU teaching so it may change.
Professor Fetzer is awesome. Very helpful.

She definitely expects her students to come to class prepared, and if you do the work (which really isn't bad at all and she's very fair/understanding with the workload), class is very interesting and engaging due to her experience and research in the field. Definitely learned a lot. READING IS A MUST.
Dr. Phenix is AMAZING. One of my favorite professors ever. I highly recommend taking her class, she cares so much about her students and is SO fun.

It was a Good class but might have been different because of COVID but lectures we kind of pointless. Lots of writing in the class which is challenging but Madame Phenix is always willing to help and gives good feedback.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Lots of homework--Get ready to read

comment: I adore Dr. Phenix. She cares greatly for her students and is always willing to help during the writing process. There was a lot of reading, but honestly some of it could be skimmed. The reading quizzes weren't worth much anyways. I highly recommend her and this class.

Dr Phenix is incredible. I hate history classes usually, but she made French history soo interesting. She is hilarious as well. A TON of reading for the class with reading quizzes in class most days, but she does it so that the discussions can be amazing. The test is a lot of writing and there is a 10 page paper at the end, but she helps so much :)

There's a lot I admire about Dr. Phenix. Her compassion for her students and her passion for her subject are at the top of the list. While the concept of studying largely from primary sources is great for authenticity, it's less great for college students doing a number of other demanding classes. FYI, she will catch your every grammatical mistake.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--Beware of pop quizzes

comment: If you plan on taking French 321, take it from Dr. Phenix. She is amazing, and although French 321 is a hard class, she makes it very doable. She constantly offers to meet with students outside of class and is willing to help out in any way she can. Take it from her! You won't regret it!

SO. MUCH. READING. She uses primary sources, which is really cool, but also takes so long, and she quizzes you on it. A lot of really good content in lectures but she doesn't post her slides or notes, so make sure to take your own. Long papers and group projects. TBH it's a toss-up if I would do it again.

Coming from 4 years of high school french and a semester of French 202, this class was not hard. Speaking tests make up a good portion of your grade, but if you prepare, she is not too hard of a grader. I probably spend 3 hours a week outside of class doing HW, preparing for tests, etc.
Dr. Phenix is great and makes class interesting, but the class is tough.
Professor Phenix is very good at teaching French and makes the rigorous requirements set forth by the Department as straightforward as possible, and she does her best to make it enjoyable as well.
ratingTags: Lots of homework--Hilarious--Beware of pop quizzes

comment: Professor Phenix is a great teacher - she is highly knowledgable about her subject areas and includes students in the lectures. This course requires lots of reading, but she makes it very interesting. She can be very intimidating. She grades you on the harsher end, but gives helpful feedback. She also is readily available outside of class if needed
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Get ready to read--Amazing lectures

comment: Dr. Phenix was great. Her class was very enjoyable and she puts in a lot of effort to make it fun. I learned a lot in her class and I'm so excited to take 322 from her. Her tests are fair. There are some tricky questions, but I feel like you'll get that no matter what class you take. WOULD HIGHLY RECOMMEND.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Participation matters--Clear grading criteria

comment: Madame Phenix is awesome! She is one of my favorite professors ever and this was one of my favorite classes ever. She is HILARIOUS and class is tons of fun. She makes learning enjoyable. It was definitely work, but she is very helpful and clear.

Dr. Phenix is AWESOME. I've had her for 321 and 322, and she is by far my favorite professor. As long as you pay attention and do your work, she's pretty clear on everything, and she's great at helping you understand French concepts and grading criteria. Class is also super fun and you'd have to make an effort to NOT learn anything in her class.

I think she is one of the best professors on campus. I had so much fun in her class! She loves to have a good time and make jokes. We were never bored! She knows the coursework can be monotonous so she would put a fun twist on things to make it more entertaining. I am going to try to keep taking classes from her as long as I can.

Loved this class. Clear expectations, interesting assignments, great in-class discussion. Uses many types of media to make class engaging. Really cares for the students and thinks about their needs. Manageable workload.

Dr. Phenix is the coolest professor ever. She always make her classes engaging and fun. I would definitely take courses with her if I could. She does assign small homework assignments after every class but they aren't too hard to stay on top of. Also she is so hilarious. If you try your best, she will appreciate your efforts.
She does everything she can to make it interesting and she's very clear.  It's predictable what is on the tests.  There is a lot of reading but it ends up being useful and she's very entertaining.

Professor Phenix is awesome! She is engaging and ABSOLUTELY hilarious. I was never bored in her class. She is really good at helping you understand grammar concepts. Your grade is pretty dependent upon being in class, participating and doing your homework. I would totally recommend Prof. Phenix!

The best thing about this class is that Prof Phenix is willing to meet with us and help us figure things out. She also makes grammar concepts really clear. Class is fun to go to. A lot of speaking practice.

Professor Phenix is new, so she doesn't have a lot of ratings, but I thought I would give one because there is only 1 review. She is a really dynamic teacher and made grammar (which I am NOT into) easy to understand. She had fun activities and gave helpful feedback.  I HIGHLY recommend her for 321!!! oh, and she speaks like a native.

Prof Phenix is really a good person and a solid teacher. The curriculum makes it tough to teach to the students needs and take time on the more difficult concepts, but she did her best to help out when she could. The tests were hard but fair. She can be a tough grader but she's willing to help and explain to you where you went wrong. I'd recommend

Dr. Kraczek was a pretty good professor! Her lectures were interesting and well prepared. Tests weren't very difficult with a little bit of studying beforehand. Attendance in mandatory so take it at a time that works well for you. The textbook isn't required, just buy the workbook and you'll be fine.
Great teacher and class! There are outside work that  takes a while so be prepared!

Dr. Kraczek was one of my favorite professors at BYU. She is so intelligent and knows so much, but she is so good at simplifying everything and making it easy to understand. She is great at answering questions and willing to help. This class was so interesting, and I loved it. It's really not very hard, but it went way more in-depth than I thought.

This class was so testimony building. It doesn't require a lot of math and is for non-majors as well. The class was super interesting and awe inspiring. I honestly think it should be a requirement for religion. Sometimes the tests and quizzes didn't quite match up to what was covered in the lecture. Overall a great class.

This is a great class and Dr. Kraczek is probably one of the best professors I've had as far as teaching methodology. She uses lecture tutorials (workbook) in class for better student retention and asks multiple choice questions in class to make sure everyone understands before moving on. Tests are moderately difficult because this is science.

After taking this class you'll always be looking at the sky. I loved this class and as long as you make an effort to pay attention, you'll get a good grade. She'll stop and ask quick questions to make sure concepts are understood. Willing to go over things again if you don't understand. Totally recommend this class! You only need to buy the wrkbook

Loved the class and the ciriculum, it was just VERY difficult. Even though I studied all the time and got good grades on the HW (which is very time consuming), I failed almost every test and the final was ridiculous. She's an amazing lecturer and the content was fantastic, but the tests and homework are ridiculously difficult

Kraczek is such an amazing professor! Easily my favorite class taken at BYU. Her lectures are easy to follow and powerpoints are posted online for your access. She takes everything really slow and weekly homework assignments are allowed two tries. She does such a good job lecturing tests are not difficult. Best class ever! Take it!!!!

Definitely exam heavy. The class average was too high, so she wrecked us all with a devastating final. So be prepared for that. Other than that the class was average, all of your assignments will be papers. Start them as soon as you can.
ratingTags: Participation matters--TEST HEAVY--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: Great guy. Makes you think and work but it's fun at the same time. Gives you the confidence to do something new and believe you can do it. I'm glad to be done with 307 but I did enjoy it while it lasted.

Dr. Rees is the man! He basically let us create our own syllabus at the beginning of the year (so that we wouldn't complain because we chose it). His tests are SO easy if you just study your lecture notes. Halfway through I stopped doing the readings because thats all we talk about in class, so you don't really need the books. Brings donuts too.
Took it as an elective, topic interesting, he is entertaining. Fun class, learned a lot, would take again.
Awesome Teacher!

Rees is a convert so he has a lot to offer on topics relating to delinquency. He offers different perspectives and makes you question the way you think without telling you you're wrong if you don't think the way he does. He's hilarious and is a very reasonable man when it comes to grades/assignments. Get to know him cause he's awesome!!

I liked the class, but I wish we'd written a paper or something - considering the material (especially since he really does love it and makes us interested in it). We had four tests and they were all multiple choice or fill in the tabs out of 30, so if you didn't get them all right - then you were already down to a A-.
Very engaging personality. Topic is interesting. Open to all ideas but keeps the class respectful to each others opinion.

Fun professor. Likes discussion and student participation. Makes you think about what you value and introduces you to new ideas without jamming them down your throat as "right". Would take again, learned a lot.
Great lectures, great personality, always there to help.

Easily one of the best teachers I've ever had! Loved his class! My favorite out of the 3 (401, 410, & 453). Not an easy course by any means, you have to work for it, but it teaches you to be financially literate and Argyle is the best. Tests can be tricky, avg. was usually around 80. Easy quiz each week. Group homework assignment each week also
Dr. Wilding is a great professor, but 311 is a cornucopia of random safety and environmental facts. Sometimes it's hard to know what's on the test.

Dr. Wilding has been my favorite teacher at BYU. He teaches super clearly and tests based on what you've been taught. He is absolutely fair about everything he does and does an excellent job of organizing an engineering class. He is a totally quality teacher, and I wish I could take more classes from him.

ChEn 311 was one of the most eye-opening classes I took at BYU. It gave me more work than I thought it should, but I also learned a lot. Dr. Wilding is such a good guy and definitely there to help you. He inspires you to be a great engineer.

I love Danielle! I loved taking her class because she made an effort to have a relationship with her students. I have never clogged before but she was always very helpful about giving tips on how to improve. She is very good dancer so its great to learn from someone with that ability. She gives plenty of time to master Choreography.
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Skip class? You won't pass.--Caring

comment: Danielle is such a sweet lady! I had no prior knowledge of clogging and she had a lot of patience with me cause it took quite some time for me to catch up with pretty much everyone else in the class. She is hilarious and engaging!
Danielle is awesome! Looked forward to her class and it saved me from going insane! Super nice, and good at explaining choreography and how to improve. Great atmosphere and fun class!
This course was a lot of fun and taught me a lot; much of how much I enjoyed it had to do with Danielle's enthusiasm for the subject and her patience with her students.

It was a great class. I loved having Danielle as a teacher; she always made it fun and enjoyable in class. She took time to make sure each of us had learned the dances and gave plenty of tutoring where needed. It was a great experience, even when coming in without any previous dance experience.
She took notes on how best to demonstrate dances for us and retooled her examples accordingly. Its a team class, so you need to be there to get credit.

Danielle taught difficult steps very well and in such a way that made them not so difficult. One dance in particular caused some stress because of its difficulty. Danielle was able to address our concerns and help with that anxiety I was feeling about the dance.

Danielle taught difficult steps very well and in such a way that made them not so difficult. One dance in particular caused some stress because of its difficulty. Danielle was able to address our concerns and help with that anxiety I was feeling about the dance. I felt that the anxiety could have been avoided if we spent a bit more time on specific
I felt like we went 1 speed in class: full speed which made it difficult to practice outside of class. The tap room has a CD player that allows CDs to be slowed down when practicing it.

She made class fun. I was not expecting beginning tap to be hard. It was my most challenging class, and I took it for fun. I'm not a dancer. Danielle helped me a lot in class and during her office hours. She saved my GPA.
Great instructor! Very fun and showed interest in students! Had loads of fun and learned a lot!

Love professor Nash, he makes class enjoyable, and will take time for you whenever you ask. The only problem with the class is the tests are based on the textbook, and often times not completely lecture based, however lectures make the content in the book clearer.
ratingTags: Accessible outside class--Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: Professor Nash is a great professor. He really understands the material he is teaching and presents it in a clear, understandable manner. He also shares stories to provide real world examples. The class is application based and does require that you read the textbook. Take notes while you read and find others in the class to study with.

Kelly Nash is a really nice person so I feel bad giving this low of a rating. However, I didn't feel like he taught very much. I honestly think about 25-30% of class was test-relevant and the rest was lawyer stories which were entertaining, but I sincerely think your grade will reflect your previous law knowledge and your ability to read textbooks.

Worst class I've taken. I studied 16 hours for the first exam, got a 66%. It's all application, meaning it's based on stuff he didn't specifically teach or wasn't all in the textbook. He's a great lawyer, but a horrible professor. If you take this class, take as few credits as possible because you'll need all the study time you can get.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Skip class? You won't pass.--TEST HEAVY

comment: I found this class to be life-changing and applicable to anyone that wants to know how to become a better executive or businessman/woman. Kelly does a phenomenal job teaching a large classroom and uses war stories from his own practice working for a prominent law firm in SLC. He genuinely wants you to succeed in life, business, and law.
The class itself was not that terribly bad, but the lectures really were just not that helpful. Just read the book and you can do fine on the test
He does about 5 in-class pop quizzes. That's really the only reason to show up. The rest can be learned independently, but the class discussions are helpful to apply a lot of the material
He's a good egg. I'm on my way to law school and it was fascinating to learn how the law affects business. Lots of good intel.
ratingTags: Get ready to read--BEWARE OF POP QUIZZES

comment: The class is pretty tough. About 20 pages of technical law ready for every class. Tests are pretty tough but if you actually do the reading and know topics on study guide, you will do fine. Recommend finding a study group. Lectures offer a lot of deep thinking, good for test prep. Must come prepared to understand.

At the beginning of the semester Professor Nash seemed great, but that quality slowly went down over the course of the semester. He wasn't well prepared for his own lectures, yet expected us to show up at every class for the randomly given iClicker quizzes. Exams are insane because there are very few resources for students to prepare for them.

Professor Nash has his own law firm. It is clear that he is passionate about the material, and is probably very successful at what he does for a living. Teaching is not what he does for a living, and that became more obvious throughout the semester. He offers very little help in preparation for exams. Pop quizzes make class attendance essential.

The tests were brutal.  He doesn't give very good advice for studying.  Honestly.  I studied so hard for all the tests and the highest grade that I got was a 74. Ended up with a B+ in the class. That tells you how big the curve is.  It was like he told you to study all the vowels, but then he tested you on the entire alphabet.

Prior to starting the course, I was a little nervous about the class and expected it to be totally boring. However, Professor Nash helped change my attitude and I had a great experience. The lectures were engaging and he added fun and humor whenever he could (e.g., on Halloween we walked through a case about Count Dracula haha). Highly recommended!
Kelly was awesome.  It was his first semester teaching and he did a great job.  It was clear that he really cared about the students and wants to see them do well.

Kelly is the bomb! He has an incredible ability to teach this very difficult subject in a simple, straightforward, and understandable way. He is consistently available, approachable, and eager to help his students learn and improve. Kelly is a great guy and such a great teacher. I HIGHLY recommend taking from him!

Kelly is an awesome professor! He does a great job at making what could be a boring class very relevant and interesting. His lectures were pretty fun and he was always willing to help. I would highly recommend him to any student required to take the class.

I am not at all the science type but Dr. V makes it really interactive and interesting. The T.A.s are always available for help with homework, there are several review sessions for each test, and he drops a bunch of quizzes and hw. It's honestly harder to do poorly in this class than it is to do well. Definitely recommend.

Honestly, this is one of the best classes at BYU, and it's all  because of this teacher. She is vivacious and super caring about her students. Even though there are a lot of assignements, they're really doable because of how she explains them, and what she expects from them. If you take this class NOT from her, you're making a mistake.

She is hands down one of the best English teachers I've ever had. She's hilarious, but also knows how to communicate some of the abstract concepts discussed in the curriculum so that they are applicable to every day life. There is a fair amount of reading, but she only expects you to give it your best shot. Take any possible class from her!

Ms.B is my favorite teacher here at BYU. Hilarious, intelligent, and does a good job at explaining very complicated topics and theories. I intentionally hunt down classes that she teaches. Like most teachers, however, you'll get the most out of her by talking to her after class (but she's always willing to talk, and responds to email fairly quick).

For more reviews search Becca Hay. I entered the first class expecting a boring, predictable writing class, but by the end of the semester I had come to love writing. Ms. B is one of the best teachers at BYU. The way she lectures - you can't look away. She is so charismatic and so funny,  and more than anything I felt like she was my friend.

I love Kevin!  He is so helpful and great at explaining difficult concepts!  He really loves his subject matter and you can tell.  He really tries hard to be friends with his students and wants to make sure they succeed.  If you try your best to complete your homework on time he gives you full credit.

Love this man. Kevin is seriously my favorite teacher at BYU! He is SO helpful because he makes sure you understand. He does a great job at making you feel smart when you participate and when you still have questions. Kevin is a way fair grader and mostly wants you to learn. I'd recommend him to anyone! Especially if you're nervous to teach math.
Kevin really cares about his students and it always willing to meet for additional help. He explains concepts clearly and is excited about math which makes the students excited.

Liu Laoshi is hands down the best professor I've had at BYU to this point. Every class period I felt like I was learning so much. She was so inspiring and the layout of the class was so organized that I felt I would have to try hard to not get an A. She cares so much about all of her students and about teaching and it reflects in each class.
She is great! So helpful! Love her!

I loved this class. There is quite a bit of homework, but none of the homework is fluff work. Liu laoshi is also really helpful-she truly cares about each student individually. She noticed my tones were often off, so she helped me make an individualized plan and extra materials to help improve them.

Liu Laoshi is great. She seemed a little intimidating for the first week or so, but after that, once you get to know her and vice versa, she is super nice and helpful. She loves the language and knows a lot about it, unlike a lot of professors who just speak the language and show up for class. Take this class!
Favorite teacher at BYU. Dailly homework that is more busy work but tests are easier than the 202 tests and worth a lot. Sweet teacher that genuinely cares about her students.

At first, Liu Laoshi seemed really strict and mean.  But after a week or so, she opened up and you could see that she really cares about her students.  She is easily my favorite Chinese teacher at BYU so far.  She has a great passion for teaching the language and is an expert teacher.  She manages class time very well. Tests not that bad.
He is a really smart guy and he knows his stuff but he is not the best at passing that information on to his students. He doesn't really stop to explain stuff.

This class was a lot of work, but I enjoyed it a lot. You will have to read a lot of science fiction, but they are pretty interesting. I took UNIV 291 and did absolutely 0 reading because the stuff they assigned was so boring. The readings for this class are fun to read. She grades the essays on the test pretty tough.
Love her!

This is an honors class for a reason (there's a lot of work). However, I really loved it, especially the culture section. The science fiction readings were all super interesting, and even though the papers were hard, I learned so much. Dr. Dean gives good feedback on tests and will help you personally if you ask.

Had her for the Honors Physical Science/Cultural Connections class. Didn't much like the class or the teacher. Feels like a high school class. Hard to see what the class is all about because it's all over the place. Wouldn't recommend

Dr. Deborah Dean is the ultimate teacher. So kind. So patient. Really wants her students to succeed. She's willing to work with you outside of class for as long as necessary in order for you to understand the assignmentmaterial. She is very loving and really puts forth her best effort to teach at the highest level. Easily my favorite prof at BYU

This class has amazing lectures and class discussions. I found it really hard to actually prepare for the tests. It has a lot of reading but the reading material is very interesting and engaging. I would take this class again. It's an awesome experience and it covers two GE credits.

This class was the best class I've taken at BYU. Professor Brown is an amazing teacher. He teaches with the spirit so much. This class brought peace to my life every time I went to it. He teaches you to study the scriptures effectively. LOVED this class!
Benjamin is a dream. He makes a class that I was avoided something enjoyable and insightful. I learned so much. He is quirky but awesome.

Dr. Ning-a-Ding is a wonderful professor. I'm sure he would have been even better with a subject he was passionate about, but he still made sure we learned and had a good experience. His goal was definitely to require the least amount of work for us. Tests weren't hard, but there was multiple choice/true false that was for some reason kinda tricky.

Great professor who taught the basics but still learned a lot. The class itself has simple concepts, and Dr. Ning is able to solidify those concepts without killing your grade. While he's not very passionate about this subject, he still helps you to see the application of it. Tests were also extremely doable.

Dr. Ning was a fantastic professor. Very kind and respectful of students, even when they would ask rhetorical questions. Lectures were very concise and clear. The material was hard, but his tests were very reasonable. One homework assignment per week that was hard but not busy. I learned a lot from him. Highly recommend!

Prof. Hawkes was a great guy. He's adjunct faculty and a lawyer by trade. Class was 2+ hours and got really long since it was all law.  Reading and attendance are necessary for a good grade. Really only 2 papers, the midterm and final that make up your grade, but extra credit is available if you participate. He's a real stickler for good writing.

Sister Merril is awesome... but the grading aspect of this class was CRAZY. like your stuff has to be perfect to get anything higher than a B. if you care about your grades at all, don't take this class!
ratingTags: Participation matters--Skip class? You won't pass.--Tough grader

comment: Audit this class if you have the choice. I was going to, but needed the credits for a scholarship. The class, teacher, and TAs were great, but they were really picky when it came to grading. The 2 exams were easy, as long as you study all the powerpoints (look for course quizlets too). They are short answer/fill in the blank, so actually study!
ratingTags: Tough Grader--Participation matters--GRADED BY FEW THINGS

comment: Great professor, but the grading was tough especially on the written portion of the tests. The average test score was a 72 and the high was an 88, which to me is ridiculous for a sewing class. I grew up sewing, but sometimes caused me more stress than my physics and PDBIO classes even though it was fun lol. avg final grade 86%
ratingTags: Get ready to read--Participation matters--LOTS OF HOMEWORK

comment: Sister Merrill is the best! Loved this class! She was always ready and willing to help, and I learned so much from her! The class was a bit rough, but so worth it!
ratingTags: Gives good feedback--Respected--Skip class? You won't pass.

comment: The class is fun, and you make good friends, but are expected to sew perfectly in order to get good scores. You have to go to open lab to finish projects and get a good grade. The TA's never seem to know what they are doing and aren't  very helpful, and neither is she. I definitely would suggest a different teacher if you want to take this class.

I loved this class. There were people in my class that had never touched a sewing machine that were sewing by the 2nd day easy. The class is so laid back and she lets us plug in our iPods to listen to whatever music we want. The other people in the class WILL become your new best friends. Lots of things to do but I wouldn't say that it is hard.

This class was so awesome! I took this class just out of the want to learn how to sew with no previous experience and it was great. Obviously you're going to have to put in some time to actually sew and learn the concepts, but they give you enough class time to do it all. Sister Merrill definitely knows her stuff!

The professor treats this class like it is ChemistryAnatomyEconEtc (classes that will actually get you a good paying job one day) Expect at the minimum 10 hours of time on this class per week. I wish this professor realized this class should just be to enjoy teaching sewing.  They expect you to already know how to sew perfectly beforehand.

SFL185R is a beginner class, and it's a pretty steep learning curve but it's still doable for a beginner. There are a ton of projects so stay on top of them and don't waste time in the lab portion of class. The TAs grade all the projects which is unfortunate because some are very strict. Sister Merrill is very helpful and kind.
He is the bomb! He loves this subject, so is always eager to teach. Can't be absent though, or you will fail.
He's very helpful, and didn't make criteria too difficult.  If you can follow what he teaches, you should do well.
It's all right class.

Hands down the best professor I've had a BYU. I took this class to fulfill a GE, and it ended up being one of the best classes I have ever taken. It was oddly incredible and eye opening. Definitely take her to fulfill a GE.

Mel is an absolute gem. She's caring, fun, and knows how to help you improve your writing and presentation skills. She really helped me out a lot, especially when I hit some roadblocks with one of the major papers. Easily the most approachable professor I've had at BYU. Highly recommend!
There a 3 major papers. The course wasn't all that interesting but she did a good job covering the material. Really cool person.

Mel was a great professor! The subject itself, writing, was not very interesting, so going to class could be boring. She told stories during class though and made sure to help everyone in any way she could.

Mel is awesome! seriously my favorite english teacher I've ever had. She cares about her students and manages to make class engaging. I shared the textbook with a friend because you don't use it a ton, but it is helpful.

Mel is just the best. I've learned more about writing from her than I have ever before. She is a very fair grader and gives great feedback. Assignments with her are fun. She's always willing to meet outside of class to give extra direction or advice. She makes class so awesome and is a real friend to her students.

My favorite part about this class is the teacher! She is really good at explaining things in ways that everyone can understand. I have learned more about writing in one semester than I have in the last six years of my life. Take this class from Mel!

I really enjoyed this class, mostly because Mrs. Henderson is really invested in everybody's experience and she tries help every student individually. She asked good questions and class discussions were great. She assigned cool reading and pushed me past my comfort zone so I actually got excited about doing my homework for this class.

Professor Reid is an AMAZING teacher. He explains concepts way better than other maths professors! His explanations are very clear and easy to understand so don't worry if you're not great at maths. He's glad to answer any questions.  You can tell he cares about all of his students and wants them all to do well on the exams. I highly recommend him!

I only participated in his test review but he was super helpful. He helped us look at each part of the problem and by the end I felt really smart. I can't say how difficult his class actually is but his teaching was great. Also, his wife brought cupcakes for the people that stayed until the end of the two hour review. That was a plus.
